# Assumption B. 

(1) There exists a universal constants $0<\bar{B}<\infty$ such that $\|\boldsymbol{\beta}\| \leq \bar{B}$;
(2) There exists a universal constants $0<\underline{B} \leq \bar{B}$ such that $\|\boldsymbol{\beta}\| \geq \underline{B}$.

Finally, we generally need to impose the first part of the following condition on the conditional second moment $Y \mid \mathbf{X}$. The second part will be needed when establishing the CAN property of our proposed estimator.

## Assumption V.

(1) We assume that $\left\|\sigma^{2}\right\|_{2}$ is bounded, where $\sigma^{2}(\cdot):=\mathbb{E}\left[Y^{2} \mid \mathbf{X}=\cdot\right]$ is the conditional second moment function of $Y$ given $\mathbf{X}$;
(2) Let $\sigma^{k}(\mathbf{x}):=\mathbb{E}\left[Y^{k} \mid \mathbf{X}=\mathbf{x}\right]$ for $k=2,4$. We assume that $\left\|\sigma^{k}\right\|_{2}$ is bounded and $\sigma^{k}(\cdot)$ is a GLM sharing the same regression coefficients $\boldsymbol{\beta}$, but with possibly different three-times differentiable link functions belonging to $L_{2}(\mathbb{P})$.

Remark 3. Assumption $\vee(2)$ is mainly made to ease exposition when we establish the CAN property of our proposed estimator (see e.g. Proposition 2 and Theorem 2). But it holds for many popular GLMs encountered in practice. For example, when $Y\left|\mathbf{X} \sim \operatorname{Ber}\left(\phi\left(\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)\right), \mathbb{E}\left[Y^{2} \mid \mathbf{X}\right]=\mathbb{E}\left[Y^{4} \mid \mathbf{X}\right]=\phi\left(\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)\right.$; when $Y\left|\mathbf{X} \sim \operatorname{Pois}\left(\phi\left(\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)\right), \mathbb{E}\left[Y^{2} \mid \mathbf{X}\right]=\phi\left(\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)+\phi^{2}\left(\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)$ and $\mathbb{E}\left[Y^{4} \mid \mathbf{X}\right]=\phi^{4}\left(\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)+6 \phi^{3}\left(\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)+$ $7 \phi^{2}\left(\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)+\phi\left(\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)$

Finally, it is worth noting that the symbols for the link function, the regression coefficients and the conditional second moment functions in the above assumptions shall be interpreted as generic notations, as in the sequel we may specialize to problem-specific symbols. For example, later in Section 4, we also use $\eta$ for the link function and $\boldsymbol{\alpha}$ for the regression coefficients.

### 2.1 Results for designs that are known to have zero mean

To gather intuition for our method, it is instructive first to consider the following assumptions.
Assumption $\mathrm{G}_{0} . \mathbf{X} \sim \mathrm{N}_{p}(\mathbf{0}, \boldsymbol{\Sigma})$ or equivalently $\mathbf{Z} \sim \mathrm{N}_{p}(\mathbf{0}, \mathbf{I})$ and $\boldsymbol{\mu}$ is known to equal $\mathbf{0}$.
Our method then essentially relies on the following result, a direct consequence of Stein's lemma or Gaussian Integration by Parts.

Lemma 1. Under Model GLM, Assumptions $\mathbb{G}_{0}, \mathbb{B}(1)$ and $\mathbb{V}(1)$, the following hold:
(1) Given any fixed vector $\boldsymbol{v} \in \mathbb{R}^{p}$ and fixed matrix $\mathbb{M} \in \mathbb{R}^{p \times p}$, the following system of moment equations holds:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \mathbb{E}\left[Y \mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \mathbb{M} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X} Y]=\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma} \mathbb{M} \boldsymbol{\Sigma} \boldsymbol{\beta} \cdot \mathbb{E}^{2}\left[\phi^{\prime}\left(\mathbf{X}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\beta}\right)\right] \\
& \mathbb{E}\left[Y \mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \mathbb{M} \boldsymbol{v}=\mathbb{E}\left[\phi^{\prime}\left(\mathbf{X}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\beta}\right)\right] \cdot \boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma} \mathbb{M} \boldsymbol{v}
\end{aligned}
$$

Consequently, choosing $\mathbb{M}=\boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1}$, we have

$$
\begin{aligned}
& m_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2}:=\mathbb{E}\left[Y \mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X} Y]=\mathbb{E}^{2}\left[\phi^{\prime}\left(\mathbf{X}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\beta}\right)\right] \cdot \gamma_{\beta}^{2}=\mathrm{f}_{1}^{2}\left(\gamma_{\beta}^{2}\right) \cdot \gamma_{\beta}^{2} \\
& m_{\mathbf{X} Y, \boldsymbol{v}}:=\mathbb{E}\left[Y \mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \boldsymbol{v}=\mathbb{E}\left[\phi^{\prime}\left(\mathbf{X}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\beta}\right)\right] \cdot \boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \boldsymbol{v} \equiv \mathrm{f}_{1}\left(\gamma_{\beta}^{2}\right) \cdot \boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \boldsymbol{v}
\end{aligned}
$$

where $\mathrm{f}_{1}(t):=\mathbb{E}\left[\phi^{\prime}(Z)\right]$ with $Z \sim \mathrm{~N}(0, t)$ for $t \geq 0$. Denote the map induced by (3a) as $\Psi_{\mathrm{GLM}_{0}, \beta}: \gamma_{\beta}^{2} \mapsto m_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2}$ and the map induced by (3) as $\Psi_{\mathrm{GLM}_{0}}:\left(\gamma_{\beta}^{2}, \boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \boldsymbol{v}\right) \mapsto\left(m_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2}, m_{\mathbf{X} Y, \boldsymbol{v}}\right)$.
(2) Further, $\Psi_{\mathrm{GLM}_{0}, \beta}$ is a diffeomorphism with $\nabla\left(\Psi_{\mathrm{GLM}_{0}, \beta}^{-1}\right)$ bounded; and the same holds for $\Psi_{\mathrm{GLM}_{0}}$. Consequently, $\gamma_{\beta}^{2}$ and $\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \boldsymbol{v}$ are identifiable in the sense that the LHS of (5) uniquely determines the value of $\left(\gamma_{\beta}^{2}, \boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \boldsymbol{v}\right)$.

We now unpack Lemma 1, with its proof deferred to the Appendix. Based on the Gaussian design and Stein's lemma, the moment equations (2) marry the moments on the LHS with certain nonlinear transformation of $\boldsymbol{\beta}$ on the RHS. The most important moment equation here is $\Psi_{\mathrm{GLM}_{0}, \beta}$ induced by (3a), that maps the quadratic form $\gamma_{\beta}^{2}$ to the moment $m_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2}$. Assumption $\mathbb{L}$ on the link function and Assumption $\mathbb{B}$ on $\gamma_{\beta}^{2}$ together ensures that $\Psi_{\mathrm{GLM}_{0}, \beta}$ is a diffeomorphism, so $\gamma_{\beta}^{2}=\Psi_{\mathrm{GLM}_{0}, \beta}^{-1}\left(m_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2}\right)$ is identified. It will also be made clear later that $\Psi_{\mathrm{GLM}_{0}, \beta}$ being a diffeomorphism entails that $\sqrt{n}$-consistent and CAN estimators of $\gamma_{\beta}^{2}$ can be constructed. After identifying $\gamma_{\beta}^{2}$, by solving (3b), $\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \boldsymbol{v}=m_{\mathbf{X} Y, \boldsymbol{v}} / \mathrm{f}_{1}\left(\gamma_{\beta}^{2}\right)$ is as well identified from the moments. Taking $\boldsymbol{v}=e_{j}$, the $j$-th standard basis in $\mathbb{R}^{p}$, the same strategy identifies $\beta_{j}$, for any $j \in[p]$.

The conclusions in Lemma 1, together with all the other identification results under Gaussian designs in this paper, do not require Assumption $\mathbb{C}$. However, the above moment equations critically rely on the Gaussianity of $\mathbf{X}$. It is natural to ask if, similar to a growing body of work studying universality for regression models under proportional asymptotics (see e.g. Bayati et al. (2015); Montanari and Saeed (2022); Montanari et al. (2023); Hu and Lu (2022); Dudeja et al. (2023b); Lahiry and Sur (2023) and references therein), one could move beyond Gaussian designs and demonstrate the universality of the above identification result. We provide a positive answer to this question following a relaxed identification criterion and shifting the burden of assumption from $\mathbf{X}$ to $\boldsymbol{\beta}$.

Definition 1 ( $\sqrt{n}$-identifiability). We say that a low-dimensional target parameter $\psi \in \mathbb{R}^{k}$, where $k$ is strictly bounded, of the underlying statistical model $\mathbb{P}$ (e.g. Model GLM) is $\sqrt{n}$-identifiable if there exists a (possibly) nonlinear map $\Psi$ from $\psi$ to certain moments defined by $\mathbb{P}$ induced by $\psi$, such that if given two different values of the target parameter, $\psi$ and $\psi^{\prime}$, such that $\left\|\psi-\psi^{\prime}\right\| \gtrsim n^{-1 / 2}$, then $\left\|\Psi(\psi)-\Psi\left(\psi^{\prime}\right)\right\| \gtrsim n^{-1 / 2}$, for sufficiently large $n$.

# Assumption $U_{0}$.

(1) $\mathbf{X}=\boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{1 / 2} \mathbf{Z}$, where $\mathbf{Z}=\left(Z_{1}, \cdots, Z_{p}\right)^{\top}$ has independent coordinates with zero mean and unit variance, and there exists a universal constant $M>0$ such that $\left\|Z_{j}\right\|_{\psi_{2}} \leq M$ for $j=1, \cdots, p$;
(2) $\sqrt{p} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{1 / 2} \boldsymbol{\beta} \stackrel{\mathrm{W}_{2}}{\rightarrow} \mathrm{~b}$ where $\mathrm{b} \sim \rho$ for some probability measure $\rho$ supported on $\mathbb{R}$ and we assume that $\rho$ has bounded first and second moments ${ }^{3}$.

Remark 4. When $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}=\mathbf{I}_{p}$, Assumption $\mathrm{U}_{0}(2)$ reduces to $\sqrt{p} \boldsymbol{\beta} \stackrel{\mathrm{W}_{2}}{\rightarrow} \mathrm{~b}$. This type of assumptions are commonly imposed. For general population covariance matrix $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$, under $\sqrt{p} \boldsymbol{\beta} \xrightarrow{\mathrm{W}_{2}} \mathrm{~b}$, the more general assumption will be met under additional assumptions on $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$.

We then have the following parallel result of Lemma 1, without assuming that $\mathbf{X}$ is Gaussian.
Lemma 2. Under the same assumptions as in Lemma 1, except with Assumption $\mathrm{G}_{0}$ replaced by Assumption $\mathrm{U}_{0}$, the system of moment equations appeared in Lemma 1 holds approximately with approximation error $O\left(p^{-3 / 4}\right)=O\left(n^{-3 / 4}\right)$ as $p \rightarrow \infty$. Thus $\gamma_{\beta}^{2}$ and $\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \boldsymbol{v}$ are $\sqrt{n}$-identifiable for any fixed vector $\boldsymbol{v} \in \mathbb{R}^{p}$.

The proof of this lemma can be found in Appendix F. Taken together, the above results motivate the following MoM-based estimator of $\gamma_{\beta}^{2}$ and $\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \boldsymbol{v}$ :

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \widehat{\gamma}_{\beta}^{2}:=\Psi_{\mathrm{GLM}_{0}, \beta}^{-1}\left(\widehat{m}_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2}\left(\widehat{m}_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2} \in \mathcal{R}_{\mathrm{GLM}_{0}, \beta}\right)\right), \quad \widehat{m}_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2}:=\mathbb{U}_{n, 2}\left[Y_{1} \mathbf{X}_{1}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbf{X}_{2} Y_{2}\right] \\
& \widehat{\boldsymbol{\beta}}^{\top} \boldsymbol{v}:=\frac{\widehat{m}_{\mathbf{X} Y, \boldsymbol{v}}}{\mathrm{f}_{1}\left(\widehat{\gamma}_{\beta}^{2}\right)}, \quad \widehat{m}_{\mathbf{X} Y, \boldsymbol{v}}:=\mathbb{U}_{n, 1}\left[Y \mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \boldsymbol{v}
\end{aligned}
$$

where $\mathcal{R}_{\mathrm{GLM}_{0}, \beta}$ denotes the range of $\Psi_{\mathrm{GLM}_{0}, \beta}$.
Since $\Psi_{\mathrm{GLM}_{0}, \beta}$ is a diffeomorphism, it is clear from the construction above that to prove $\sqrt{n}$ consistency of $\widehat{\gamma}_{\beta}^{2}$ and $\widehat{\boldsymbol{\beta}}^{\top} \boldsymbol{v}$ one needs to verify $\max \left\{\operatorname{var}\left(\widehat{m}_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2}\right), \operatorname{var}\left(\widehat{m}_{\mathbf{X} Y, \boldsymbol{v}}\right)\right\}=O(1 / n)$, which is indeed the case (see Appendix F). We next summarize the above reasoning as the following proposition.
Proposition 1. Under the Assumptions of Lemma 1 or Lemma 2, the following hold:

$$
\sqrt{n}\left(\widehat{\gamma}_{\beta}^{2}-\gamma_{\beta}^{2}\right)=O_{\mathbb{P}}(1), \text { and for any } j=1, \ldots, p, \sqrt{n}\left(\widehat{\boldsymbol{\beta}}^{\top} \boldsymbol{v}-\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \boldsymbol{v}\right)=O_{\mathbb{P}}(1)
$$

In fact, as $n \rightarrow \infty$, we can consider a more precise result and record that the above MoM-based estimators are CAN under the Gaussian design and some additional regularity conditions.

Proposition 2. Under Model GLM, Assumptions $\mathrm{G}_{0}$, B and V , if we further assume that $\|\boldsymbol{\beta}\|_{f(\boldsymbol{\Sigma})}^{2}$ converges to some nontrivial limit for $f(\boldsymbol{\Sigma})=\boldsymbol{\Sigma}, \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{2}, \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{3}$, we have

$$
\sqrt{n}\left(\widehat{\beta}-\beta_{j}\right) \xrightarrow{\mathcal{E}} \mathrm{N}\left(0, \nu_{j}^{2}\right)
$$

for some constant $\nu_{j}^{2}>0$ for $j=1, \cdots, p$ and

$$
\sqrt{n}\left(\widehat{\gamma}_{\beta}^{2}-\gamma_{\beta}^{2}\right) \xrightarrow{\mathcal{E}} \mathrm{N}\left(0, \nu^{2}\right)
$$

for some constant $\nu^{2}>0$.

[^0]
[^0]:    ${ }^{3}$ Here, given a random vector $\mathrm{A} \in \mathbb{R}^{p}$ and a random variable $\mathrm{a} \in \mathbb{R}$, the notation $\mathrm{A} \stackrel{\mathrm{W}_{2}}{\rightarrow} \mathrm{a}$ means that the empirical distribution over the coordinates of A converges in $\mathrm{W}_{8}$-distance (8-Wasserstein distance) to the distribution of a, as $p \rightarrow \infty$.

Remark 5. It is noteworthy that Assumption $\mathrm{B}(2)$ is imposed mainly to ensure that the event $\left(\widetilde{m}_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2} \in \mathcal{R}_{\mathrm{GLM}_{0}, \beta}\right)$ holds with probability converging to 1 such that the constraint does not affect the asymptotic distribution of the $U$-statistic estimator $\widetilde{m}_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2}$. We conjecture that it is possible to relax this assumption by a more precise analysis of the asymptotic behavior of $\widetilde{m}_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2}$ close to the boundary $\|\boldsymbol{\beta}\|=0$, which is left for future work.

Remark 6. The CAN property of the proposed MoM-based estimators relies on two separate results: (1) the CLT of first-order and second-order $U$-statistics, followed from the results in Bhattacharya and Ghosh (1992) (see Appendix E for a complete proof) (2) $\Psi_{\mathrm{GLM}_{0}, \beta}$ is a diffeomorphism, and its inverse map, $\Psi_{\mathrm{GLM}_{0}, \beta}^{-1}$, has bounded derivative so the Delta Method can be applied.

Remark 7. In Proposition 2 (and similar results related to the CAN property of our proposed estimator in the sequel), we need some extra assumptions on the convergence of inner products such as $\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} f(\boldsymbol{\Sigma}) \boldsymbol{\beta}$. It is worth mentioning that the assumption imposed in the main text might not be tight. By speculating the derivations in Appendix E, one only needs either $\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma} \boldsymbol{\beta}$ or $\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{3} \boldsymbol{\beta}$ to converge. But to avoid unnecessary technical complications that are irrelevant to the main theme of the paper, we decide not to pursue further in this direction. Also, one can easily find sufficient conditions to establish the convergence of such quantities. As a simple example, when $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}=\mathbf{I}_{p}$ and $\boldsymbol{\beta}$ satisfies Assumption $\mathrm{U}_{0}$, we immediately have $\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} f(\boldsymbol{\Sigma}) \boldsymbol{\beta}$ to converge.

In addition, we also impose an extra condition on $\mathbb{E}\left[Y^{4}[\mathbf{X}]\right.$ via Assumption $\vee$. This assumption is to ensure that certain re-scaled fourth moments of the $U$-statistics vanish to zero as $n \rightarrow \infty$, which is required based on the proof strategy that we currently employ (see Lemma 10 and Proposition 5 in Appendix E).

Finally, we do not explicitly specify the form of the asymptotic variance, which is complicated due to the use of second-order $U$-statistics. Nonetheless, in our previous work (Appendix A. 8 of Liu et al. (2024)), consistent variance estimators based on tweaking the nonparametric bootstrap have been developed and can be used to conduct inference; also see Section 6.1 for a brief discussion and Appendix H. 5 for its finite-sample performance.

Remark 8. At this point, readers might wonder why we consider moments such as $m_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2}$ that involves $\mathbf{X}$. When $\boldsymbol{\mu} \equiv \mathbf{0}, Y \in\{0,1\}$ and $\phi(\cdot)=\operatorname{expit}(\cdot)$, it is obvious that all the moments of $Y$ reduce to $\mathbb{E}[Y] \equiv 0.5$. Thus without leveraging information of $\mathbf{X}$, it is generally impossible to identify functionals of $\boldsymbol{\beta}$. This is why the moment-based estimator in Sawaya et al. (2023), based only on $\mathbb{E}[Y]$, cannot be directly applied to logistic or probit regression.

# 2.2 Results for designs with unknown and possibly non-zero means 

Next, we show that the zero covariate-mean condition is not essential to our moment-based approach, but a larger system of moment equations is required to identify relevant parameters in GLMs. The development closely mirrors that of the previous section when $\boldsymbol{\mu}$ is known to equal $\mathbf{0}$. As before, we first set the stage under Gaussian designs.

Assumption G. $\mathbf{X} \sim \mathrm{N}_{p}(\boldsymbol{\mu}, \boldsymbol{\Sigma})$ or equivalently $\mathbf{Z} \sim \mathrm{N}_{p}(\mathbf{0}, \mathbf{I})$.
For short, we let $\boldsymbol{\nu}=\left(\nu_{1}, \cdots, \nu_{p}\right)^{\top}:=\boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \boldsymbol{\mu}$. The following lemma then generalizes Lemma 1 to the case of Gaussian designs with unknown mean $\boldsymbol{\mu}$.

Lemma 3. Under Model GLM, Assumptions G, B(1), and V(1):

(1) The following system of moment equations holds:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& m_{Y}:=\mathbb{E}[Y]=\mathrm{f}_{0}\left(\lambda_{\beta}, \gamma_{\beta}^{2}\right) \\
& m_{\mathbf{X}, 2}:=\mathbb{E}\left[\mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X}]=\boldsymbol{\mu}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \boldsymbol{\mu} \\
& m_{\mathbf{X} Y, \mathbf{X}}:=\mathbb{E}\left[Y \mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X}]=m_{Y} \cdot m_{\mathbf{X}, 2}+\mathrm{f}_{1}\left(\lambda_{\beta}, \gamma_{\beta}^{2}\right) \cdot \lambda_{\beta} \\
& m_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2}:=\mathbb{E}\left[Y \mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X} Y]=m_{Y}^{2} \cdot m_{\mathbf{X}, 2}+\mathrm{f}_{1}^{2}\left(\lambda_{\beta}, \gamma_{\beta}^{2}\right) \cdot \gamma_{\beta}^{2}+2 \cdot m_{Y} \cdot \mathrm{f}_{1}\left(\lambda_{\beta}, \gamma_{\beta}^{2}\right) \cdot \lambda_{\beta} \\
& m_{\nu_{j}}:=\mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X}]^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbf{e}_{j}=\boldsymbol{\mu}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbf{e}_{j}=\boldsymbol{\nu}^{\top} \mathbf{e}_{j}=\nu_{j} \\
& m_{\beta_{j}}:=\mathbb{E}\left[Y \mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbf{e}_{j}=\mathrm{f}_{0}\left(\lambda_{\beta}, \gamma_{\beta}^{2}\right) \cdot \nu_{j}+\mathrm{f}_{1}\left(\lambda_{\beta}, \gamma_{\beta}^{2}\right) \cdot \beta_{j}
\end{aligned}
$$

where $\mathrm{f}_{k}(s, t):=\mathbb{E}\left[\phi^{(k)}(Z)\right]$ with $Z \sim \mathrm{~N}(s, t)$. Denote the forward map induced by this system as

$$
\Psi_{\mathrm{GLM}}=\left(\Psi_{\mathrm{GLM}, 1}, \Psi_{\mathrm{GLM}, 2}, \cdots \Psi_{\mathrm{GLM}, 6}\right)^{\top}:\left(\lambda_{\beta}, \gamma_{\beta}^{2}\right)^{\top} \mapsto\left(m_{Y}, m_{\mathbf{X}, 2}, \cdots, m_{\beta_{j}}\right)^{\top}
$$

(2) Further, the first four equations of (5), denoted as $\Psi_{\mathrm{GLM},[4]}$, can be reduced to

$$
\begin{aligned}
& m_{1}:=m_{Y}=\mathrm{f}_{0}\left(\lambda_{\beta}, \gamma_{\beta}^{2}\right) \\
& m_{2}:=m_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2}+m_{Y}^{2} \cdot m_{\mathbf{X}, 2}-2 \cdot m_{Y} \cdot m_{\mathbf{X} Y, \mathbf{X}}=\mathrm{f}_{1}^{2}\left(\lambda_{\beta}, \gamma_{\beta}^{2}\right) \cdot \gamma_{\beta}^{2}
\end{aligned}
$$

Denote the forward map induced by (6) as $\Psi_{\mathrm{GLM}, \beta}=\left(\Psi_{\mathrm{GLM}, \beta, 1}, \Psi_{\mathrm{GLM}, \beta, 2}\right)^{\top}:\left(\lambda_{\beta}, \gamma_{\beta}^{2}\right)^{\top} \mapsto$ $\left(m_{1}, m_{2}\right)^{\top}$. Then $\Psi_{\mathrm{GLM}, \beta}$ is a diffeomorphism with $\nabla\left(\Psi_{\mathrm{GLM}, \beta}^{-1}\right)$ bounded. Consequently, $\lambda_{\beta}, \gamma_{\beta}^{2}$, and $\beta_{j}$ are identifiable.

The proof of Lemma 3 can be found in Appendix B and Appendix D.1. To establish universality of Lemma 3 beyond Gaussian designs, we need to first generalize Assumption $\mathrm{U}_{0}$ to Assumption U below.

# Assumption U. 

(1) $\mathbf{X}=\boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{1 / 2} \mathbf{Z}+\boldsymbol{\mu}$, where $\mathbf{Z}=\left(Z_{1}, \cdots, Z_{p}\right)^{\top}$ has independent coordinates with zero mean, unit variance, and $\max _{j=1}^{p}\left\|Z_{j}\right\|_{\psi_{2}} \leq M$ for some universal constant $M>0$;
(2) $\sqrt{p} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{1 / 2} \boldsymbol{\beta} \xrightarrow{W_{2}} \mathrm{~b}$ and $\sqrt{p} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1 / 2} \boldsymbol{\mu} \xrightarrow{W_{2}} \mathrm{u}$ where $\mathrm{b} \sim \rho$ and $\mathrm{u} \sim \varrho$ respectively for some probability measures $\rho$ and $\varrho$ supported on $\mathbb{R}$ and we assume that both $\rho$ and $\varrho$ have bounded first and second moments.

Lemma 2 can then be generalized as follows, the proof of which can be found in Appendix F.
Lemma 4. Under the same assumptions as in Lemma 3, except with Assumption G replaced by Assumption U, the systems of moment equations appeared in Lemma 3 hold approximately with approximation error $O\left(p^{-3 / 4}\right)=O\left(n^{-3 / 4}\right)$ as $n \rightarrow \infty$.

When the distribution of $\mathbf{X}$ is unknown and one passes to universality after using a Gaussian identification strategy, we conjecture that certain delocalization conditions, such as Assumption $U(2)$ on the (transformed) regression coefficients and covariate mean vector, are necessary. In fact, universality can fail when one starts from a Gaussian identification strategy and Assumption $U(2)$ is violated - as demonstrated via the numerical experiments related to Figures 11 and 12; see Section 5 for more details.

Remark 9. Compared to the special case of knowing $\boldsymbol{\mu} \equiv \mathbf{0}$ in Section 2.1, it requires extra moment equations (5a) to (5c) to identify $\gamma_{\beta}^{2}$, together with the linear form $\lambda_{\beta}$. When it is known that $\boldsymbol{\mu}=\mathbf{0},(5 \mathrm{a}),(5 \mathrm{~b})$, and (5c), respectively, reduce to constants $1 / 2,0$, and 0 .

Remark 10. When the law of $\mathbf{X}$ is absolutely continuous with density $p$ with respect to the Lebesgue measure is (partially) known but non-Gaussian, one could leverage the following generalized Stein's identity (and its higher-order analogues) to obtain similar moment equations

$$
\mathbb{E}[f(\mathbf{X}) s(\mathbf{X})]+\mathbb{E}\left[f^{\prime}(\mathbf{X})\right]=0
$$

where $s(\mathbf{x}):=\nabla p(\mathbf{x}) / p(\mathbf{x}): \mathbb{R}^{p} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^{p}$ is the Stein's score function and $f: \mathbb{R}^{p} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$ is any differentiable function such that both sides of the above identity exist. We do not explore these generalizations in this paper and keep it as potential future directions.

Gathering the development thus far, we can construct the following estimator of $\left(\lambda_{\beta}, \gamma_{\beta}^{2}\right)$ based on $\Psi_{\mathrm{GLM}, \beta}$ and its inverse map $\Psi_{\mathrm{GLM}, \beta}^{-1}$ :

$$
\left(\widehat{\lambda}_{\beta}, \widehat{\gamma}_{\beta}^{2}\right):=\Psi_{\mathrm{GLM}, \beta}^{-1}\left(\widehat{m}_{1}\left\{\widehat{m}_{1} \in \mathcal{R}_{\mathrm{GLM}, \beta, 1}\right\}, \widehat{m}_{2}\left\{\widehat{m}_{2} \in \mathcal{R}_{\mathrm{GLM}, \beta, 2}\right\}\right)
$$

where

$$
\begin{gathered}
\widehat{m}_{1}:=\widehat{m}_{Y}:=\mathbb{U}_{n, 1}[Y], \quad \widehat{m}_{2}:=\widehat{m}_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2}+\widehat{m}_{Y}^{2} \cdot \widehat{m}_{\mathbf{X}, 2}-2 \cdot \widehat{m}_{Y} \cdot \widehat{m}_{\mathbf{X} Y, \mathbf{X}} \\
\text { and } \widehat{m}_{\mathbf{X}, 2}:=\mathbb{U}_{n, 2}\left[\mathbf{X}_{1}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbf{X}_{2}\right], \widehat{m}_{\mathbf{X} Y, \mathbf{X}}:=\mathbb{U}_{n, 2}\left[Y_{1} \mathbf{X}_{1}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbf{X}_{2}\right], \widehat{m}_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2}:=\mathbb{U}_{n, 2}\left[Y_{1} \mathbf{X}_{1}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbf{X}_{2} Y_{2}\right]
\end{gathered}
$$

With $\left(\widehat{\lambda}_{\beta}, \widehat{\gamma}_{\beta}^{2}\right)$, one can estimate $\beta_{j}$ by simply solving (5e) to (5f):

$$
\widehat{\beta}_{j}:=\frac{\widehat{m}_{\beta_{j}}-\mathrm{f}_{0}\left(\widehat{\lambda}_{\beta}, \widehat{\gamma}_{\beta}^{2}\right) \cdot \widehat{m}_{\nu_{j}}}{\mathrm{f}_{1}\left(\widehat{\lambda}_{\beta}, \widehat{\gamma}_{\beta}^{2}\right)}
$$

where

$$
\widehat{m}_{\nu_{j}}:=\mathbb{U}_{n, 1}\left[\mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbf{e}_{j}, \quad \widehat{m}_{\beta_{j}}:=\mathbb{U}_{n, 1}\left[Y \mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbf{e}_{j}
$$

Theorem 1. Under the Assumptions of Lemma 3 or Lemma 4, the following hold:

$$
\sqrt{n}\left(\widehat{\lambda}_{\beta}-\lambda_{\beta}\right)=O_{\mathbb{P}}(1), \sqrt{n}\left(\widehat{\gamma}_{\beta}^{2}-\gamma_{\beta}^{2}\right)=O_{\mathbb{P}}(1), \text { and for any } j=1, \cdots, p, \sqrt{n}\left(\widehat{\beta}_{j}-\beta_{j}\right)=O_{\mathbb{P}}(1)
$$

The final result in this section generalizes Proposition 2 for the CAN property of our proposed estimators to the case where $\boldsymbol{\mu}$ is unknown and possibly non-zero.

Theorem 2. Under Model GLM, Assumptions G, B and V, if we further assume that $\left\langle\mathbf{v}_{1}, \mathbf{v}_{2}\right\rangle_{f(\boldsymbol{\Sigma})}$ converges to some nontrivial limit for $f(\boldsymbol{\Sigma})=\boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1}, \boldsymbol{\Sigma}, \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{2}, \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{3}$ for $\mathbf{v}_{1}, \mathbf{v}_{2} \in\{\boldsymbol{\mu}, \boldsymbol{\beta}\}$, we have

$$
\sqrt{n}\left(\widehat{\beta}_{j}-\beta_{j}\right) \xrightarrow{\mathcal{E}} \mathrm{N}\left(0, \nu_{j}^{2}\right)
$$

for some constant $\nu_{j}^{2}>0$ for $j=1, \cdots, p$ and

$$
\sqrt{n}\left(\widehat{\gamma}_{\beta}^{2}-\gamma_{\beta}^{2}\right) \xrightarrow{\mathcal{E}} \mathrm{N}\left(0, \nu^{2}\right)
$$

for some constant $\nu^{2}>0$.

In the proof of the above theorem in Appendix E.2, we unpack the conditions of the theorem further. On a higher level, convergence of inner products $\left\langle\mathbf{v}_{1}, \mathbf{v}_{2}\right\rangle_{f(\boldsymbol{\Sigma})}$ to certain nontrivial limits relates to whether the asymptotic variances of moment estimators based on $U$-statistics, after scaled by $\sqrt{n}$, converge to nontrivial limits. For statistical inference, one could construct standard Wald intervals by estimating the asymptotic variances in Theorem 2 by the bootstrap method developed in Liu et al. (2024). The performance of bootstrap variance estimators will be assessed in Appendix H.5.
Remark 11 (On the scalings between $p$ and $n$ ). Even though we focus on the asymptotic regime where $p$ scales proportionally with $n$, it is worth noting that our proposed estimators can achieve consistency even when $p \gg n$, as long as $p=o\left(n^{2}\right)$. This is because the variances of our $U$-statisticbased moment estimators are generally of order $\frac{1}{n} \vee \frac{p}{n^{2}}$. Asymptotic normality also holds with a different scaling factor $n / \sqrt{p}$ instead of $n^{1 / 2}$, by applying results from Bhattacharya and Ghosh (1992).

Remark 12 (Data-driven Approximate Message Passing Schemes for GLMs). Before proceeding, we take a detour to present one immediate application of our MoM-based method for inference in GLMs. Further applications of our method can be found in later Section 4. For logistic regression, i.e. Model (GLM) with $\phi \equiv$ expit, Sur and Candès (2019) (and in a more general form, Salehi et al. (2019)) showed the following: for $\widehat{\boldsymbol{\beta}}_{\text {MLE }} \equiv\left(\widehat{\beta}_{\text {MLE }, 1}, \cdots, \widehat{\beta}_{\text {MLE }, p}\right)^{\top}$ the Maximum Likelihood Estimator (MLE) of $\boldsymbol{\beta}$, letting $\left(Z_{0}, Z_{1}, Z_{2}, Z_{3}\right)^{\top} \sim \mathrm{N}_{4}\left(\mathbf{0}, \mathbf{I}_{4}\right)$, one has

$$
\frac{1}{p} \sum_{j=1}^{p} h\left(\widehat{\beta}_{\mathrm{MLE}, j}-\bar{\alpha} \beta_{j}, \beta_{j}\right) \xrightarrow{\mathrm{F}} \mathbb{E}\left[h\left(\bar{\sigma} Z_{0}, \mathrm{~b}\right)\right]
$$

where $(\bar{\alpha}, \bar{\sigma}, \bar{\gamma})$ is the solution to the following fixed point equations

$$
\left\{\begin{aligned}
\delta^{2} \bar{\sigma}^{2} & =2 \mathbb{E}\left[\phi\left(-\kappa Z_{1}\right)\left(\bar{\gamma} \phi\left(\operatorname{prox}[\bar{\gamma} \Phi]\left(\kappa \bar{\alpha} Z_{1}+\sqrt{\delta} \bar{\sigma} Z_{2}\right)\right)\right)^{2}\right] \\
0 & =2 \mathbb{E}\left[\phi\left(-\kappa Z_{1}\right) Z_{1} \bar{\gamma} \phi\left(\operatorname{prox}[\bar{\gamma} \Phi]\left(\kappa \bar{\alpha} Z_{1}+\sqrt{\delta} \bar{\sigma} Z_{2}\right)\right)\right] \\
1-\delta & =2 \mathbb{E}\left[\phi\left(-\kappa Z_{1}\right) \operatorname{prox}[\bar{\gamma} \Phi]^{\prime}\left(\kappa \bar{\alpha} Z_{1}+\sqrt{\delta} \bar{\sigma} Z_{2}\right)\right]
\end{aligned}\right.
$$

Here $\Phi(\cdot):=\int_{-\infty} \phi(t) \mathrm{d} t$ is the anti-derivative of $\phi, \kappa:=\mathbb{E} \mathrm{b}^{2} \equiv p^{-1} \sum_{j=1}^{p} \mathbb{E}\left[\beta_{j}^{2}\right]$ and prox denotes the proximal operator with $\operatorname{prox}[h]^{\prime}(\cdot)$ being the first derivative of $\operatorname{prox}[h](\cdot)$. Since $\kappa$ is unknown, two different methods have been proposed: ProbeFrontier by Sur and Candès (2019) leveraging and SLOE by Yadlowsky et al. (2021) using a reparameterization of (9) in terms of $p^{-1} \sum_{j=1}^{p} \widehat{\beta}_{\text {MLE }, j}^{2}$ instead of $\kappa$. The proposed MoM-based method evidently offers another approach to estimating $\kappa$ from data. This is also the problem that Sawaya et al. (2023) try to solve. However, as mentioned in the Introduction, the approach in Sawaya et al. (2023) only applies to asymmetric link functions because it does not rely on $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$.

# 3 The Case of Unknown Population Covariance 

In this section, we demonstrate that knowing $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$ is not essential to the proposed MoM method in the previous section. To ease presentation, we focus on the case of knowing $\boldsymbol{\mu} \equiv \mathbf{0}$. We will discuss briefly in Appendix G.2.3 for completeness how to estimate $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$ in the general case where both $\boldsymbol{\mu}$ and $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$ are unknown. In the accompanying GitHub repository, we also implement the proposed method for this more general scenario.

# 3.1 A Gaussian-centric approach when $p<n$ 

As mentioned in the Introduction, our parameter identification and estimation strategies rely on the knowledge of $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$ under the proportional asymptotic regime. In this section, we consider relaxing this assumption under Gaussian designs. To simplify our argument, we assume that $n$ is even and partition all $n$ samples into two equal-sized parts $I_{1}:=[n / 2]$ and $I_{2}:=[(n / 2+1): 2 n]$. We use the second partition $I_{2}$ to estimate $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$ by the following rescaled sample Gram matrix

$$
\tilde{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}}:=\frac{1}{\frac{n}{2}-p-1} \sum_{j \in I_{2}} \mathbf{X}_{j} \mathbf{X}_{j}^{\top}
$$

We conjecture that it is possible to attain $\sqrt{n}$-consistency without using sample splitting to estimate $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$ (Liu and Li, 2023), but we decide to leave the analysis to a future work.

When $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$ is unknown, we propose to estimate $\gamma_{\beta}^{2}$ as in (4), except that $\widehat{m}_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2}$ is replaced by

$$
\widehat{m}_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2}:=\frac{1}{\frac{n}{2}\left(\frac{n}{2}-1\right)} \sum_{i_{1} \neq i_{2} \in I_{1}} Y_{i_{1}} \mathbf{X}_{i_{1}}^{\top} \tilde{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}}^{-1} \mathbf{X}_{i_{2}} Y_{i_{2}}
$$

It is worth mentioning that, only in this Section and Appendix G.2, $\widehat{m}_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2}$ takes the above form.
It is easy to see that $\widehat{m}_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2}$ is an unbiased estimator of $m_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2}$. Moreover, we have the following parallel results to Proposition 1, the proof of which can be found in Appendix G.2.
Proposition 3. Under Assumptions of Lemma 1, when $p+3<n / 2$ and $p / n \rightarrow c$ for some fixed $c<1$, the following hold:

$$
\sqrt{n}\left(\tilde{\gamma}_{\beta}^{2}-\gamma_{\beta}^{2}\right)=O_{\mathrm{F}}(1), \text { and for any } j=1, \ldots, p, \sqrt{n}\left(\bar{\beta}_{j}-\beta_{j}\right)=O_{\mathrm{F}}(1)
$$

The additional assumption $p+3<n / 2$ is a result of computing the covariance between any two elements of a random matrix drawn from the Inverse-Wishart distribution; see Lemma 15 for more details. It is worth noting that Proposition 3 can also be generalized beyond Gaussian designs by using universality-type results on (inverse) sample Gram matrices, e.g. related advances in Dereziński et al. (2021) and Dereziński et al. (2022).

Remark 13. Under linear models, one can in fact adapt the estimators of Guo and Cheng (2022) for unknown $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$ by leveraging the linearity structure; for details, see Appendix G.1.

Furthermore, when $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$ is unknown, without estimating $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$, one can still test the null hypothesis $H_{0}: \boldsymbol{\beta}=\mathbf{0}$ by simply estimating the quantity $\mathbb{E}\left[Y \mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X} Y]=\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{2} \boldsymbol{\beta}$, which equals zero if and only if $H_{0}$ is true, using a $U$-statistic $\mathbb{U}_{n, 2}\left(Y_{1} \mathbf{X}_{1}^{\top} \mathbf{X}_{2} Y_{2}\right)$ without the knowledge of $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$.

### 3.2 An alternative approach that works when $p \geq n$

The approach considered in the previous section no longer applies to the case of $p \geq n$ (or more precisely, $p \geq n / 2$ when sample splitting is employed), as the sample Gram matrix is not invertible. Here we discuss an alternative approach using Higher-Order $U$-statistics, first considered in Kong and Valiant (2018).

The idea is to approximate $m_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2}=\mathbb{E}\left[Y \mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X} Y]$, the moment with reciprocal, by Chebyshev polynomials (DeVore and Lorentz, 1993):

$$
\widetilde{m}_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2, J}:=\sum_{l=0}^{J} c_{l} m_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2}^{(l)}, \text { where } m_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2}^{(l)}:=\mathbb{E}\left[Y \mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{l} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X} Y]
$$

up to order $J$ to be specified later. How to specify the Chebyshev polynomial coefficients $\left\{c_{l}, l=\right.$ $0, \cdots, J\}$ will be deferred to Appendix G.2.2. Note that $m_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2}^{(l)}$ can be unbiasedly estimated by the following $(l+2)$-th order $U$-statistic:

$$
\widehat{m}_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2}^{(l)}:=\frac{(n-(l+2))!}{n!} \sum_{1 \leq i_{1} \neq \cdots \neq i_{l+2} \leq n} Y_{i_{1}} \mathbf{X}_{i_{1}}^{T}\left\{\prod_{s=3}^{l+2} \mathbf{X}_{i_{s}} \mathbf{X}_{i_{s}}^{T}\right\} \mathbf{X}_{i_{2}} Y_{i_{2}}
$$

with variance of order $\frac{1}{n}\left(\frac{p}{n}\right)^{l+1}$. Hence we consider the following estimator of $\gamma_{\beta}^{2}$ :

$$
\widehat{m}_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2, J(n)}:=\sum_{l=0}^{J(n)} c_{l} \widehat{m}_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2}^{(l)}
$$

where $J(n) \asymp(\log n)^{c}$ for some $c$ strictly less than 1 . One could approximate the other involved moments and define $\widehat{\gamma}_{\beta, J(n)}^{2}$ and $\widehat{\beta}_{j, J(n)}$ for $j=1, \cdots, p$ similarly.

This alternative approach based on higher-order $U$-statistics also works in principle when $p<n$, but has inflated variance compared to the proposal in the previous section solely based on 2nd-order $U$-statistics. When $p \geq n, \widehat{\gamma}_{\beta, J(n)}^{2}$ and $\widehat{\beta}_{j, J(n)}$ are still consistent for $\gamma_{\beta}^{2}$ and $\beta_{j}$ as shown in the Proposition below. The proof is deferred to Appendix G.2.2. Here we only record the consistency without providing the concrete convergence rate. We conjecture that the tight convergence rate should be slower than $n^{-1 / 2}$ but a more precise characterization demands a much more careful control of the variance of higher-order $U$-statistics and is thus beyond the scope of this article.

Proposition 4. Under Assumptions of Lemma 1 or Lemma 2, the following hold:

$$
\widehat{\gamma}_{\beta, J(n)}^{2}-\gamma_{\beta}^{2}=o_{\mathbb{P}}(1), \text { and for any } j=1, \ldots, p, \widehat{\beta}_{j, J(n)}-\beta_{j}=o_{\mathbb{P}}(1)
$$

Remark 14. $\widehat{m}_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2}$ defined in (10) with the prefactor $\left(\frac{n}{2}-p-1\right) / \frac{n}{2}$ removed is nothing but the empirical second-order influence function of the functional $\mathbb{E}\left[Y \mathbf{X}^{\top} \mid \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X} Y]\right.$, to our knowledge first developed in Liu et al. (2017). In Liu et al. (2017), however, they did not make distributional assumptions on $\mathbf{X}$ such as Assumption $\mathbb{G}_{0}$ or even Assumption $\mathbb{G}$, resulting in more complicated higher-order $U$-statistics for correcting the bias due to estimating $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$ by $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$. In particular, the order can diverge to infinity as $n \rightarrow \infty$. Gaussian designs significantly simplify the diverging-order $U$-statistic estimator to a rescaled second-order $U$-statistic. An interesting question to further explore is which other types of assumptions on $\mathbf{X}$, e.g. right rotationally invariant designs ( Li and Sur, 2023), can also reduce higher-order $U$-statistics to simpler second-order $U$-statistics.

When $p \geq n$, here we follow the higher-order $U$-statistic construction of Kong and Valiant (2018) to avoid estimating $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1}$. Kong and Valiant (2018) also developed a polynomial-time algorithm for computing higher-order $U$-statistics, but only when the $U$-statistic kernels are symmetric. When $\boldsymbol{\mu}$ is unknown, the involved $U$-statistics have asymmetric kernels (see Section 2.2 and Appendix G.2.3), making the computation a much more challenging problem that we plan to address in a separate paper. We mention in passing that Robins et al. (2016) also constructed higher-order $U$-statistics, with order diverging at rate $\sqrt{\log n}$, to estimate quantities such as $m_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2}$. Their estimators, however, first estimate the density function of $\mathbf{X}$ and then estimate $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1}$ by numerical integration with respect to the estimated density function. Higher-order $U$-statistics are employed to reduce the bias due to density estimation, rather than approximating $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1}$ by polynomials. We leave the study of statistical implications of this subtle difference to a future paper.

# 4 Inference in Observational Studies 

In this section, we appeal to the discussions in previous parts to develop estimators for some popular quantities arising in the context of observational studies. We only present theoretical results when the covariates under study have a Gaussian distribution with known covariance $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$. Results with unknown $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$ can be derived similarly by following the arguments in Section 3. The universality of the proposed procedure can be established by analogous arguments in the proof of Lemma 4, and hence omitted to avoid repetition and simplify exposition. The examples we discuss here are popular members of what is now known as the class of Doubly-Robust Functionals (Robins et al., 2008; Rotnitzky et al., 2021; Chernozhukov et al., 2022) where in high dimensional instances of the problem practitioners often aim to model the two high dimensional relevant nuisance parameters of the underlying model through flexible GLMs. Although we consider specific and most popular examples in this class, a potential future research avenue is to extend the results in this section to the entire class of Doubly-Robust Functionals characterized in Rotnitzky et al. (2021).

We divide our discussions into three subsections: estimation of causal effects of binary treatment in linear structural models, estimating quantities under missing data, and estimating generalized covariance measure (or equivalently expected conditional covariance (Liu et al., 2024)) that have gained popularity in recent literature on conditional independence testing (Shah and Peters, 2020; Christgau et al., 2023). Throughout this section, we assume that we have access to $n$ i.i.d. copies of the triples $\left(\mathbf{X}_{i}, A_{i}, Y_{i}\right)_{i=1}^{n} \stackrel{\text { i.i.d. }}{\sim} \mathbb{P}$ where $\mathbf{X}$ is the covariates or the design matrix, except for Section 4.2 with a minor modification. The approaches considered in Section 3 to estimate $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1}$ from data apply to all examples here without any conceptual challenges. Consequently, we only present results assuming that $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$ is known.

### 4.1 Causal Effect of a Binary Treatment under Linear Structural Causal Models

First, we consider the task of estimating the causal effect of a binary treatment $A \in\{0,1\}$ on an outcome $Y$ in a linear structural model. Our goal is to estimate the parameter $\psi$ in the following data generating model with the outcome regression a linear model and the propensity score a GLM with link $\phi$.

$$
Y=\psi \cdot A+\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \mathbf{X}+\varepsilon, \quad A \mid \mathbf{X} \sim \operatorname{Ber}\left(\phi\left(\boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)\right)
$$

where $\varepsilon$ has mean zero and bounded second moment given $\mathbf{X}, A$.
For convenience, we let $\boldsymbol{\mu}_{1}:=\mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X} A], \lambda_{\alpha, 1}:=\boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\mu}_{1}$ and $\lambda_{\beta, 1}:=\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\mu}_{1}$. The following lemma characterizes the moment equations under Model CE, and the derivation can be found in Appendix D.

Lemma 5. Under Model $\mathbb{C E}$, Assumptions $\mathbb{G}, \mathbb{B}(1)$ on both $\boldsymbol{\alpha}$ and $\boldsymbol{\beta}$, and $\mathbb{V}(1)$ on both $A \mid \mathbf{X}$ and $Y \mid \mathbf{X}, A$, the following system of moment equations holds:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& m_{A}:=\mathbb{E}[A] \\
& m_{Y}:=\mathbb{E}[Y]=\psi \cdot m_{A}+\lambda_{\beta} \\
& m_{A Y}:=\mathbb{E}[A Y]=\left(\psi+\lambda_{\beta}\right) \cdot m_{A}+\gamma_{\alpha, \beta} \cdot \mathrm{f}_{1}\left(\lambda_{\alpha}, \gamma_{\alpha}^{2}\right) \\
& m_{\mathbf{X}, 2}:=\mathbb{E}\left[\mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X}]=\boldsymbol{\mu}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \boldsymbol{\mu} \\
& m_{\mathbf{X} A, \mathbf{X}}:=\mathbb{E}\left[A \mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X}]=\boldsymbol{\mu}_{1}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \boldsymbol{\mu} \\
& m_{\mathbf{X} A, 2}:=\mathbb{E}\left[A \mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X} A]=m_{A} \cdot m_{\mathbf{X} A, \mathbf{X}}+\mathrm{f}_{1}\left(\lambda_{\alpha}, \gamma_{\alpha}^{2}\right) \cdot \lambda_{\alpha, 1}
\end{aligned}
$$

$$
\begin{aligned}
& m_{\mathbf{X}, \mathbf{X} Y}:=\mathbb{E}\left[A \mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X} Y]=\psi \cdot m_{\mathbf{X}, 2}+\lambda_{\beta, 1} \\
& m_{\mathbf{X} A Y, \mathbf{X} A}:=\mathbb{E}\left[Y A \mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X} A]=\psi \cdot m_{\mathbf{X} A, 2}+m_{A} \cdot \lambda_{\beta, 1}+\lambda_{\beta} \cdot m_{A} \cdot m_{\mathbf{X} A, \mathbf{X}} \\
& \quad+\mathrm{f}_{1}\left(\lambda_{\alpha}, \gamma_{\alpha}^{2}\right) \cdot\left(\lambda_{\beta} \cdot \lambda_{\alpha, 1}+\gamma_{\alpha, \beta} \cdot m_{\mathbf{X}, \mathbf{X} A}\right)+\mathrm{f}_{2}\left(\lambda_{\alpha}, \gamma_{\alpha}^{2}\right) \cdot \gamma_{\alpha, \beta} \cdot \lambda_{\alpha, 1}
\end{aligned}
$$

where the definition of $\mathrm{f}_{k}$ appears in the statement of Lemma 3.
In addition, denote the forward map induced by the RHS of the above system as

$$
\begin{aligned}
\Psi_{\mathrm{CE}}:= & \left(\Psi_{\mathrm{CE}, 1}, \cdots, \Psi_{\mathrm{CE}, 8}\right):\left(\psi, \lambda_{\alpha}, \gamma_{\alpha}^{2}, \lambda_{\beta}, \gamma_{\alpha, \beta}, \lambda_{\alpha, 1}, \lambda_{\beta, 1}\right) \\
& \mapsto\left(m_{A}, m_{Y}, m_{A Y}, m_{\mathbf{X}, \mathbf{X} A}, m_{\mathbf{X} A, 2}, m_{\mathbf{X} A, \mathbf{X} Y}, m_{\mathbf{X} A Y, \mathbf{X} A}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

In particular, $\Psi_{\mathrm{CE}}$ is a diffeomorphism. As a consequence, $\psi$, together with $\left(\lambda_{\alpha}, \gamma_{\alpha}^{2}, \lambda_{\beta}, \gamma_{\alpha, \beta}, \lambda_{\alpha, 1}, \lambda_{\beta, 1}\right)$, is identifiable from the above system of moment equations.

The proof of the above lemma can be found in Appendix C.1. As a direct corollary of Lemma 5, we can construct $\sqrt{n}$-consistent and CAN estimator of $\psi$ as follows.

$$
\widehat{\psi}=\Psi_{\mathrm{CE}, 1}^{-1}\left(\widehat{m}_{A}, \widehat{m}_{Y}, \widehat{m}_{A Y}, \widehat{m}_{\mathbf{X}, \mathbf{X} A}, \widehat{m}_{\mathbf{X} A, 2}, \widehat{m}_{\mathbf{X} A, \mathbf{X} Y}, \widehat{m}_{\mathbf{X} A Y, \mathbf{X} A}\right)
$$

where all the moment estimators are constructed in a similar fashion to those in (8).
Theorem 3. Under Model CE, Assumptions G, B(1) on both $\boldsymbol{\alpha}$ and $\boldsymbol{\beta}$, and $\mathrm{V}(1)$ on both $A \mid \mathbf{X}$ and $Y \mid \mathbf{X}, A$, we have

$$
\sqrt{n}(\widehat{\psi}-\psi)=O_{\mathbb{P}}(1)
$$

Alternatively, under Model CE with $\varepsilon$ being independent from $\mathbf{X}, A$, Assumptions G, B on both $\boldsymbol{\alpha}$ and $\boldsymbol{\beta}$, and $\vee$ on both $A \mid \mathbf{X}$ and $Y \mid \mathbf{X}, A$, if we further assume that $\left\langle\mathbf{v}_{1}, \mathbf{v}_{2}\right\rangle_{f(\boldsymbol{\Sigma})}$ converges to some nontrivial limit for $f(\boldsymbol{\Sigma})=\boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1}, \boldsymbol{\Sigma}, \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{2}, \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{3}$ for $\mathbf{v}_{1}, \mathbf{v}_{2} \in\{\boldsymbol{\mu}, \boldsymbol{\alpha}, \boldsymbol{\beta}\}$, we have

$$
\sqrt{n}(\widehat{\psi}-\psi) \xrightarrow{\mathcal{E}} \mathrm{N}\left(0, \nu^{2}\right)
$$

for some constant $\nu^{2}>0$.
To our knowledge, the above is the first result for CAN estimation for average treatment effect type quantities under the proportional asymptotic regime where $p>n$ is allowed. In this regard, Jiang et al. (2024); Yadlowsky (2022) operate under $p<n$ regime, without knowing $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$, owing to their reliance on ordinary least squares type estimator for the outcome regression. Our results close this gap in the literature under the knowledge of $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$. The proofs of CAN for all the examples in Section 4, including Theorem 3, can be found in Appendix E. The CAN property of $\widehat{\psi}$ is a corollary of the CAN property established for the estimators of the linear and quadratic forms in Theorem 2.

# 4.2 Mean Estimation with Missing Data under Missing-At-Random (MAR) 

In this section, we take $A \in\{0,1\}$ and only observe $Y$ if $A=1$. Our goal is to estimate $\psi:=\mathbb{E}[Y]$. For $\psi$ to be identifiable from the observed data, the missing data mechanism is assumed to be Missing-At-Random (MAR). More specifically, we assume that $\mathbb{P}$ is defined and parameterized as follows:

$$
A \mid \mathbf{X}=\mathbf{x} \sim \operatorname{Ber}\left(\eta\left(\boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \mathbf{x}\right)\right) \text { with } \eta\left(\boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \cdot\right) \in(\underline{c}, \bar{c}), Y=\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \mathbf{X}+\varepsilon
$$

where $\varepsilon$ has mean zero and bounded second moment and is independent of $A$ and $\mathbf{X}$ and $\underline{c}, \bar{c}$ are two universal constants satisfying $0<\underline{c}<\bar{c}<1$. As in Celentano and Wainwright (2023), we assume that only $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$ is known. Under Model MAR,

$$
\psi \equiv \boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\mu} \equiv \mathbb{E}\left[\frac{A Y}{\eta\left(\boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)}\right]
$$

This problem is isomorphic to that of estimating treatment specific mean from observational studies under no unmeasured confounding.

Let $\mathrm{g}_{j}(t):=\mathbb{E}\left[\eta^{(j)}(Z)\right]$, where $Z \sim \mathrm{~N}\left(\lambda_{\alpha}, \gamma_{\alpha}^{2}\right)$ with $\lambda_{\alpha}:=\boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\mu}$ and $\gamma_{\alpha}^{2}:=\|\boldsymbol{\alpha}\|_{\Sigma}^{2}$. We also define $\gamma_{\alpha, \beta}:=\boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma} \boldsymbol{\beta}=\langle\boldsymbol{\alpha}, \boldsymbol{\beta}\rangle_{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}}$. The following lemma characterizes the moment equations under Model MAR, and the derivation can again be found in Appendix D.

Lemma 6. Under Model MAR, Assumptions G, B(1) on both $\boldsymbol{\alpha}$ and $\boldsymbol{\beta}$, and $\mathrm{V}(1)$ on both $A \mid \mathbf{X}$ and $Y \mid \mathbf{X}$, the following system of moment equations holds:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& m_{A}:=\mathbb{E}[A] \\
& m_{\mathbf{X}, 2}:=\mathbb{E}\left[\mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X}]=\boldsymbol{\mu}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \boldsymbol{\mu} \\
& m_{\mathbf{X}, \mathbf{X}}:=\mathbb{E}\left[A \mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \boldsymbol{\mu}=m_{A} \cdot m_{\mathbf{X}, 2}+\mathrm{f}_{1}\left(\lambda_{\alpha}, \gamma_{\alpha}^{2}\right) \cdot \lambda_{\alpha} \\
& m_{\mathbf{X} A, 2}:=\mathbb{E}\left[A \mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X} A]=m_{A}^{2} \cdot m_{\mathbf{X}, 2}+\mathrm{f}_{1}^{2}\left(\lambda_{\alpha}, \gamma_{\alpha}^{2}\right) \cdot \gamma_{\alpha}^{2}+2 \cdot m_{A} \cdot \mathrm{f}_{1}\left(\lambda_{\alpha}, \gamma_{\alpha}^{2}\right) \cdot \lambda_{\alpha} \\
& m_{A Y}:=\mathbb{E}[A Y]=m_{A} \cdot \psi+\mathrm{f}_{1}\left(\lambda_{\alpha}, \gamma_{\alpha}^{2}\right) \cdot \gamma_{\alpha, \beta} \\
& m_{\mathbf{X} A Y, \mathbf{X}}:=\mathbb{E}\left[Y A \mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \boldsymbol{\mu}=\left(m_{A}+m_{\mathbf{X} A, \mathbf{X}}\right) \cdot \psi+\left\{m_{\mathbf{X}, 2} \cdot \mathrm{f}_{1}\left(\lambda_{\alpha}, \gamma_{\alpha}^{2}\right)+\mathrm{f}_{2}\left(\lambda_{\alpha}, \gamma_{\alpha}^{2}\right) \cdot \lambda_{\alpha}\right\} \cdot \gamma_{\alpha, \beta}
\end{aligned}
$$

where the definition of $\mathrm{f}_{k}$ appears in the statement of Lemma 3.
In addition, denote the forward map induced by the RHS of the above system as

$$
\begin{aligned}
\Psi_{\mathrm{MAR}}:= & \left(\Psi_{\mathrm{MAR}, 1}, \cdots, \Psi_{\mathrm{MAR}, 6}\right):\left(\psi, \lambda_{\alpha}, \gamma_{\alpha}^{2}, \gamma_{\alpha, \beta}\right) \\
& \mapsto\left(m_{A}, m_{\mathbf{X}, 2}, m_{\mathbf{X} A, \mathbf{X}}, m_{\mathbf{X} A, 2}, m_{A Y}, m_{\mathbf{X} A Y, \mathbf{X}}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

In particular, $\Psi_{\text {MAR }}$ is a diffeomorphism. As a consequence, $\psi$, together with $\left(\lambda_{\alpha}, \gamma_{\alpha}^{2}, \gamma_{\alpha, \beta}\right)$, is identifiable from the above system of moment equations.

Remark 15. The system of moment equations for identifying $\psi$ is not unique. For example, one could also replace $m_{\mathbf{X} A Y, \mathbf{X}}$ by $m_{\mathbf{X} A Y, \mathbf{X} A}$, which leads to the following identity:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& m_{\mathbf{X} A Y, \mathbf{X} A}:=\mathbb{E}\left[A Y \mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X} A] \\
= & \left\{m_{A}^{2} \cdot m_{\mathbf{X}, 2}+2 m_{A} \cdot \mathrm{f}_{1}\left(\lambda_{\alpha}, \gamma_{\alpha}^{2}\right) \cdot \lambda_{\alpha}+m_{A}^{2}+\mathrm{f}_{1}^{2}\left(\lambda_{\alpha}, \gamma_{\alpha}^{2}\right) \cdot \gamma_{\alpha}^{2}\right\} \cdot \psi \\
& +\left\{\begin{array}{c}
m_{A} \cdot\left(\mathrm{f}_{1}\left(\lambda_{\alpha}, \gamma_{\alpha}^{2}\right) \cdot m_{\mathbf{X}, 2}+\mathrm{f}_{2}\left(\lambda_{\alpha}, \gamma_{\alpha}^{2}\right) \cdot \lambda_{\alpha}\right) \\
+\mathrm{f}_{1}^{2}\left(\lambda_{\alpha}, \gamma_{\alpha}^{2}\right) \cdot \lambda_{\alpha}+\mathrm{f}_{1}\left(\lambda_{\alpha}, \gamma_{\alpha}^{2}\right) \mathrm{f}_{2}\left(\lambda_{\alpha}, \gamma_{\alpha}^{2}\right) \cdot \gamma_{\alpha}^{2}
\end{array}\right\} \cdot \gamma_{\alpha, \beta}
\end{aligned}
$$

Combining (11f') with either (12e) or (12f) identifies $\psi$ by solving the corresponding two linear equations. Which combination leads to more efficient estimators of $\psi$ is left for future work to study.

If one is also interested in $\operatorname{var}(Y)$, the system (12) can be further augmented by adding the moment equation for $m_{\mathbf{X} A Y, 2}:=\mathbb{E}\left[Y A \mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X} A Y]$.

The proof of the above lemma can be found in Appendix C.2. As a direct corollary of Lemma 6, we can construct $\sqrt{n}$-consistent and CAN estimator of $\psi$ as follows.

$$
\widehat{\psi}=\Psi_{\mathbf{M A R}, 1}^{-1}\left(\widehat{m}_{A}, \widehat{m}_{\mathbf{X}, 2}, \widehat{m}_{\mathbf{X} A, \mathbf{X}}, \widehat{m}_{\mathbf{X} A, 2}, \widehat{m}_{A Y}, \widehat{m}_{\mathbf{X} A Y, \mathbf{X}}\right)
$$

where all the moment estimators are constructed in a similar fashion to those in (8).
Theorem 4. Under Model MAR, Assumptions G, B(1) on both $\boldsymbol{\alpha}$ and $\boldsymbol{\beta}$, and $\mathrm{V}(1)$ on both $A \mid \mathbf{X}$ and $Y \mid \mathbf{X}$, we have

$$
\sqrt{n}(\widehat{\psi}-\psi)=O_{\mathbb{P}}(1)
$$

Alternatively, under Model MAR, Assumptions G, B on both $\boldsymbol{\alpha}$ and $\boldsymbol{\beta}$, and V on both $A \mid \mathbf{X}$ and $Y \mid \mathbf{X}$, if we further assume that $\left\langle\mathbf{v}_{1}, \mathbf{v}_{2}\right\rangle_{f(\boldsymbol{\Sigma})}$ converges to some nontrivial limit for $f(\boldsymbol{\Sigma})=\boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1}, \boldsymbol{\Sigma}, \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{2}, \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{3}$ for $\mathbf{v}_{1}, \mathbf{v}_{2} \in\{\boldsymbol{\mu}, \boldsymbol{\alpha}, \boldsymbol{\beta}\}$, we have

$$
\sqrt{n}(\widehat{\psi}-\psi) \xrightarrow{\mathcal{E}} \mathrm{N}\left(0, \nu^{2}\right)
$$

for some constant $\nu^{2}>0$.
For estimating $\psi$ in Model MAR, as we mentioned in the Introduction, Celentano and Wainwright (2023) proposed estimators that resemble debiased Lasso in the proportional asymptotic regime, under the Gaussian design with known population covariance matrix $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$. We compare the numerical performance of our estimator $\widehat{\psi}$ and those of Celentano and Wainwright (2023) later in Section 5.2.

# 4.3 Estimation of the Generalized Covariance Measure (GCM) 

In this section, we assume that $\mathbb{P}$ is defined and parameterized as follows:

$$
\mathbb{E}[A \mid \mathbf{X}=\mathbf{x}]=\eta\left(\boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \mathbf{x}\right), \mathbb{E}[Y \mid \mathbf{X}=\mathbf{x}]=\phi\left(\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \mathbf{x}\right)
$$

where both $A$ and $Y$ have bounded second moments. We also let $\sigma_{A}^{2}(\cdot):=\operatorname{var}(A \mid \mathbf{X}=\cdot), \sigma_{Y}^{2}(\cdot):=$ $\operatorname{var}(Y \mid \mathbf{X}=\cdot)$ and $\sigma_{A, Y}(\cdot):=\operatorname{cov}(A, Y \mid \mathbf{X}=\cdot)$. Shah and Peters (2020) proposed to test $H_{0}: Y \Perp A \mid \mathbf{X}$ by estimating the parameter $\mathbb{E}\left[\left(Y-\phi\left(\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)\right)\left(A-\eta\left(\mathbf{X}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\alpha}\right)\right)\right]$, often referred to as the expected conditional covariance or Generalized Covariance Measure (GCM). Without loss of generality, we take the target of inference as

$$
\psi:=\mathbb{E}\left[\eta\left(\boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right) \phi\left(\mathbf{X}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\beta}\right)\right]
$$

The following lemma characterizes the moment equations under Model GCM, and the derivation can again be found in Appendix D.

Lemma 7. Under Model GCM, Assumptions G, B(1) on both $\boldsymbol{\alpha}$ and $\boldsymbol{\beta}$, and $\mathrm{V}(1)$ on both $A \mid \mathbf{X}$ and $Y \mid \mathbf{X}$, the following system of moment equations holds:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& m_{A}:=\mathbb{E}[A] \\
& m_{Y}:=\mathbb{E}[Y] \\
& m_{\mathbf{X}, 2}:=\mathbb{E}\left[\mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X}]=\boldsymbol{\mu}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \boldsymbol{\mu}
\end{aligned}
$$

$$
\begin{aligned}
& m_{\mathbf{X}, \mathbf{X}}:=\mathbb{E}\left[A \mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X}]=m_{A} \cdot m_{\mathbf{X}, 2}+\mathrm{g}_{1}\left(\lambda_{\alpha}, \gamma_{\alpha}^{2}\right) \cdot \lambda_{\alpha} \\
& m_{\mathbf{X} Y, \mathbf{X}}:=\mathbb{E}\left[Y \mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X}]=m_{Y} \cdot m_{\mathbf{X}, 2}+\mathrm{f}_{1}\left(\lambda_{\beta}, \gamma_{\beta}^{2}\right) \cdot \lambda_{\beta} \\
& m_{\mathbf{X} A, 2}:=\mathbb{E}\left[A \mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X} A]=m_{A}^{2} \cdot m_{\mathbf{X}, 2}+\mathrm{g}_{1}^{2}\left(\lambda_{\alpha}, \gamma_{\alpha}^{2}\right) \cdot \gamma_{\alpha}^{2}+2 \cdot m_{A} \cdot \mathrm{~g}_{1}\left(\lambda_{\alpha}, \gamma_{\alpha}^{2}\right) \cdot \lambda_{\alpha} \\
& m_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2}:=\mathbb{E}\left[Y \mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X} Y]=m_{Y}^{2} \cdot m_{\mathbf{X}, 2}+\mathrm{f}_{1}^{2}\left(\lambda_{\beta}, \gamma_{\beta}^{2}\right) \cdot \gamma_{\beta}^{2}+2 \cdot m_{Y} \cdot \mathrm{f}_{1}\left(\lambda_{\beta}, \gamma_{\beta}^{2}\right) \cdot \lambda_{\beta} \\
& m_{\mathbf{X} A, \mathbf{X} Y}:=\mathbb{E}\left[A \mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X} Y]=m_{A} \cdot m_{Y} \cdot m_{\mathbf{X}, 2}+m_{A} \cdot \mathrm{f}_{1}\left(\lambda_{\beta}, \gamma_{\beta}^{2}\right) \cdot \lambda_{\beta} \\
& +m_{Y} \cdot \mathrm{~g}_{1}\left(\lambda_{\alpha}, \gamma_{\alpha}^{2}\right) \cdot \lambda_{\alpha}+\mathrm{g}_{1}\left(\lambda_{\alpha}, \gamma_{\alpha}^{2}\right) \cdot \mathrm{f}_{1}\left(\lambda_{\beta}, \gamma_{\beta}^{2}\right) \cdot \gamma_{\alpha, \beta}
\end{aligned}
$$

where the definition of $\mathrm{f}_{k}$ appears in the statement of Lemma 3.
In addition, denote the forward map induced by the RHS of the above system as

$$
\begin{aligned}
\Psi_{\mathrm{GCM}}:= & \left(\Psi_{\mathrm{GCM}, 1}, \cdots, \Psi_{\mathrm{GCM}, 8}\right):\left(\lambda_{\alpha}, \gamma_{\alpha}^{2}, \lambda_{\beta}, \gamma_{\beta}^{2}, \gamma_{\alpha, \beta}\right) \\
& \mapsto\left(m_{A}, m_{Y}, m_{\mathbf{X}, 2}, m_{\mathbf{X} A, \mathbf{X}}, m_{\mathbf{X} Y, \mathbf{X}}, m_{\mathbf{X} A, 2}, m_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2}, m_{\mathbf{X} A, \mathbf{X} Y}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

In particular, $\Psi_{\mathrm{GCM}}$ is a diffeomorphism. As a consequence, $\psi$, together with $\left(\lambda_{\alpha}, \gamma_{\alpha}^{2}, \lambda_{\beta}, \gamma_{\beta}^{2}, \gamma_{\alpha, \beta}\right)$, is identifiable from the above system of moment equations.

The proof of the above lemma can be found in Appendix C.3. As a direct corollary of Lemma 7, we can construct $\sqrt{n}$-consistent and CAN estimator of $\psi$ as follows. Let

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \widehat{\psi}:=\mathbb{E}\left[\eta\left(Z_{1}\right) \phi\left(Z_{2}\right], \text { where }\binom{Z_{1}}{Z_{2}} \sim \mathrm{~N}_{2}\left(\left(\begin{array}{l}
\widehat{\lambda}_{\alpha} \\
\widehat{\lambda}_{\beta}
\end{array}\right),\left(\begin{array}{ll}
\widehat{\gamma}_{\alpha}^{2} & \widehat{\gamma}_{\alpha, \beta} \\
\widehat{\gamma}_{\alpha, \beta} & \widehat{\gamma}_{\beta}^{2}
\end{array}\right)\right), \text { and } \\
& \left(\widehat{\lambda}_{\alpha}, \widehat{\gamma}_{\alpha}^{2}, \widehat{\lambda}_{\beta}, \widehat{\gamma}_{\beta}^{2}, \widehat{\gamma}_{\alpha, \beta}\right):=\Psi_{\mathrm{GCM}}^{-1}\left(\widehat{m}_{A}, \widehat{m}_{Y}, \widehat{m}_{\mathbf{X}, 2}, \widehat{m}_{\mathbf{X} A, \mathbf{X}}, \widehat{m}_{\mathbf{X} Y, \mathbf{X}}, \widehat{m}_{\mathbf{X} A, 2}, \widehat{m}_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2}, \widehat{m}_{\mathbf{X} A, \mathbf{X} Y}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

where all the moment estimators are constructed in a similar fashion to those in (8).
To establish $\sqrt{n}$-consistency and CAN of our proposed estimator, we also need to impose the following condition on the conditional covariance function of $A, Y$ given $\mathbf{X}$.

# Assumption Cov. 

(1) We assume that $\left\|\sigma_{A, Y}(\cdot)\right\|_{2}$ is bounded;
(2) We assume that the conditional covariance of $A, Y$ given $\mathbf{X}$ is also a GLM with link function $\zeta$ :

$$
\sigma_{A, Y}(\mathbf{X})=\zeta\left(\boldsymbol{\theta}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right) \text { almost surely }
$$

such that $\zeta$ is three-times differentiable and the first to third derivatives of $\zeta$, together with $\zeta$ itself, are integrable with respect to the law of $\mathbf{X}$ and the integrals are all strictly bounded by some universal constant.

Theorem 5. Under Model GCM, Assumptions G, B(1) on both $\boldsymbol{\alpha}$ and $\boldsymbol{\beta}, \mathrm{V}(1)$ on both $A \mid \mathbf{X}$ and $Y \mid \mathbf{X}$, and $\operatorname{Cov}(1)$, we have

$$
\sqrt{n}(\widehat{\psi}-\psi)=O_{\mathbb{P}}(1)
$$

Alternatively, under Model GCM, Assumptions G, B on both $\boldsymbol{\alpha}$ and $\boldsymbol{\beta}, \mathrm{V}$ on both $A \mid \mathbf{X}$ and $Y \mid \mathbf{X}$, and Cov, if we further assume that $\left\langle\mathbf{v}_{1}, \mathbf{v}_{2}\right\rangle_{f(\boldsymbol{\Sigma})}$ converges to some nontrivial limit for $f(\boldsymbol{\Sigma})=$ $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1}, \boldsymbol{\Sigma}, \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{2}, \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{3}$ for $\mathbf{v}_{1}, \mathbf{v}_{2} \in\{\boldsymbol{\mu}, \boldsymbol{\alpha}, \boldsymbol{\beta}, \boldsymbol{\theta}\}$, we have

$$
\sqrt{n}(\widehat{\psi}-\psi) \xrightarrow{\mathcal{L}} \mathrm{N}\left(0, \nu^{2}\right)
$$

for some constant $\nu^{2}>0$.

Since we do not assume $Y \Perp A \mid \mathbf{X}$ and GLMs are only specified for $A \mid \mathbf{X}$ and $Y \mid \mathbf{X}$, Assumption $\operatorname{Cov}(1)$ is needed for $\sqrt{n}$-consistency because the variances of the moment estimators based on $U$-statistics involve terms such as $\mathbb{E}[A Y \mathbf{X}]$. This is in contrast to the previous two examples. In Section 4.1, GLMs are specified for variational independent components $A \mid \mathbf{X}$ and $Y \mid \mathbf{X}, A$ of the joint observed-data distribution, whereas in Section 4.2, we assume that $Y \Perp A \mid \mathbf{X}$.

# 5 Numerical Experiments 

In this section, we verify our theory via extensive numerical experiments. We consider two types of problems. The first problem, studied in Section 5.1, is on estimating linear and quadratic forms of regression coefficients $\boldsymbol{\alpha}$ of a GLM between the response $A$ and baseline covariates $\mathbf{X}$. The second problem, studied in Section 5.2, is on estimating the mean of a response $Y$ subject to missingness under Model MAR. As mentioned, the latter problem is also isomorphic to estimating treatment specific mean from observational studies under no unmeasured confounding. All the results in the numerical experiments are based on 500 Monte Carlos. The dimension-sample size ratio $p / n$ is fixed at 1.2 in Section 5.1 and 1.25 in Section 5.2. Appendix H contains additional simulation results that are complementary to those reported here in the main text. We always assume that $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$ is known except that in Appendix H. 4 we conduct simulations to evaluate the performance of our proposed estimators in Section 3.1 when knowing neither $\boldsymbol{\mu}$ nor $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$. The bootstrap variance estimators mentioned right after Theorem 2 are assessed in Appendix H.5.

For all the histograms and normal quantile-quantile plots reported in this section and in Appendix H, we choose the numerical experiment with $n=5000$. The R codes for replicating the numerical experiments can be found in this GitHub repository.

### 5.1 Linear and quadratic forms of GLMs

We consider several different experiment settings. But across different settings, the common Data Generating Process (DGP) can be described as follows: $A \mid \mathbf{X} \sim \operatorname{Ber}\left(\operatorname{expt}\left(\boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)\right)$ where the goal is to estimate a single coordinate $\alpha_{1}$ and the quadratic form $\gamma_{\alpha}^{2}=\boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma} \boldsymbol{\alpha}$. Throughout this section, we set the true value of the quadratic form as $\mathbb{E}\left(\gamma_{\alpha}^{2}\right) \equiv 1$. The true value of $\alpha_{1}$ may vary across different settings. The DGPs vary in the following aspects:

- $\mathbf{X}_{i} \stackrel{\text { i.i.d. }}{\sim} \mathrm{N}_{p}(\boldsymbol{\mu}, \boldsymbol{\Sigma})$ with $\boldsymbol{\mu} \equiv \mathbf{0}$ and $\boldsymbol{\Sigma} \equiv \mathbf{I}_{p}$ for $i=1, \cdots, n$ (Settings $1 \& 2$ ); $\mathbf{X}_{i, j} \stackrel{\text { i.i.d. }}{\sim} \operatorname{Rad}(1 / 2)$ for $i=1, \cdots, n$ and $j=1, \cdots, p$ where Rad denotes the Rademacher distribution (Settings 3 \& 4). The two cases, though, share the same population mean and covariance matrix.
- $\boldsymbol{\alpha}$ is dense in the sense that we draw $\boldsymbol{\alpha}=\left(\alpha_{1}, \cdots, \alpha_{p}\right) \stackrel{\text { i.i.d. }}{\sim}$ Uniform $([-\sqrt{3 / p}, \sqrt{3 / p}])$ (Settings $1 \& 3)$; $\boldsymbol{\alpha}$ is sparse in the sense that $s=\sqrt{p}$ out of $p$ coordinates are non-zero and each non-zero coefficient equals $p^{-1 / 4}$ (Settings $2 \& 4$ ). Due to the similarity between results for dense and sparse configurations, we defer the figures for the sparse configuration case to Appendix H.1.
- We also vary the sample sizes as $n=1000,2000, \cdots, 5000$. We note that Setting 2 corresponds to the simulation setting described in Section 6.3 of Bellec (2024).

In each setting, for the problem of estimating certain single coordinate, we compare our MoMbased estimators against the methods of Bellec (2024), which debiases the initial estimator $\widehat{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}_{\text {init }}$

of $\boldsymbol{\alpha}$ using their main Theorem 4.1. We do not further compare different estimators of $\lambda_{\alpha}$ and $\gamma_{\alpha}^{2}$ as the methodology in Bellec (2024) is for linear form $\mathbf{v}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\alpha}$ with known direction $\mathbf{v}$, not directly applicable here. For simplicity, we use ridge regression to compute $\widehat{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}_{\text {init }}$. For the tuning parameter $\lambda$ in ridge regression, due to large running time, We choose twelve different values of $\lambda$ ranging from 0.05 to 10 , equally spaced on a logarithmic scale.

We summarize the results of the numerical experiments below. For single coordinates of $\boldsymbol{\alpha}$, we arbitrarily pick $\alpha_{1}$ and $\alpha_{100}$ to present the simulation results.

- When the design is Gaussian (Settings $1 \& 2$, Figures 1, 2, 7 and 8), Figures 1 shows that our proposed MoM-based estimator of $\alpha_{1}$ and $\alpha_{100}$ generally have similar $\sqrt{n} \times$ bias, variance, and mean squared error to the estimator proposed in Bellec (2024). Moreover, Figures 2 and 8 showcase the histograms and normal quantile-quantile plots of the $U$-statistic-based moment estimators and estimators of $\lambda_{\alpha}, \gamma_{\alpha}^{2}, \alpha_{1}$ and $\alpha_{100}$ by solving the moment system (5). It is clear from these figures that the sampling distributions of both the $U$-statistic-based moment estimators and our estimators $\alpha_{1}$ and $\gamma_{\alpha}^{2}$ are close to the Gaussian distribution, further confirming by our theoretical results on the GAN property of our proposed MoM-based estimators.
- When the design is Rademacher (Settings $3 \& 4$, Figures 3, 4, 9 and 10), we observe similar results to those in the Gaussian settings. Therefore, under certain conditions on the design and the regression coefficients, our identification and estimation strategies based on Gaussian designs continue to be applicable - demonstrating the universality of our proposed procedure. Interestingly, the debiased estimator also exhibits universality, which deserves a further theoretical investigation. It is worth noting that although Setting 4 concerns sparse regression coefficients, the number of non-zero coefficients is large and the values of non-zero coefficients are the same, so numerically our MoM-based estimators work still fine. In Appendix H.2, we showcase a different simulation setting, in which only one coordinate of the coefficients is non-zero; there the results show that the Gaussian-based identification and estimation strategies no longer produce consistent estimators.

# 5.2 Mean estimation with missing data under MAR 

For the problem of estimating the mean of a response $Y$ under Model MAR, we also consider several different settings. We first describe the common part of the DGP: the data is generated according to Model MAR, with $\mathbf{X}_{i} \stackrel{\text { i.i.d. }}{\sim} \mathrm{N}_{p}\left(\mathbf{0}, \mathbf{I}_{p}\right)$ for $i=1, \cdots, n$. We take $\mathbb{E}[A \mid \mathbf{X}]=0.1+0.9 \cdot \operatorname{expit}\left(\mathbf{X}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\alpha}\right)$, as in Celentano and Wainwright (2023). Here the true value of the target parameter $\psi$ is 0 because $\mathbf{X}$ has mean zero. We take the outcome noise $\varepsilon \sim \mathrm{N}\left(0, \sigma^{2}\right)$ with $\sigma=0.2$. The sample size varies from 100 to 10000 . We compare our proposed MoM-based estimator $\hat{\psi}$ with the two estimators proposed in Celentano and Wainwright (2023), respectively termed as "Oracle ASCW" and "Empirical SCA". For these alternative estimators, initial estimates based on Ridge are also used, With the tuning parameter $\lambda$ taking 50 values ranging from $[0.01,10]$ with equal steps on a logarithmic scale. We refer readers to Celentano and Wainwright (2023) for the details of these two alternative estimators; here we simply implement the R code provided in the GitHub repository provided by the authors of Celentano and Wainwright (2023).

We also consider two different configurations for the regression coefficients $\boldsymbol{\alpha}$ and $\boldsymbol{\beta}$. In Setting 1 (Figures $5-6$ ), we consider dense regression coefficients, where both $\boldsymbol{\alpha}$ and $\boldsymbol{\beta}$ are drawn i.i.d.

It is clear from these figures that the sampling distributions of both the $U$-statistic-based moment estimators and of the estimators of the target parameter $\psi$, together with $\lambda_{\alpha}, \gamma_{\alpha}^{2}, \gamma_{\alpha, \beta}$ (the byproducts of the system (12)), are close to the Gaussian distribution.

# 6 Discussion 

This paper proposes Method-of-Moments (MoM) estimators of functionals of the regression coefficients in high-dimensional GLMs under the proportional asymptotic regime, in the most part assuming Gaussian designs with known population covariance matrix $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$, following the current trend of literature. We demonstrate promising theoretical and numerical results about the MoM estimators. However, we emphasize that a more delicate comparison between our proposed approach

![img-5.jpeg](img-5.jpeg)

Figure 6: Simulation results for Setting 1 (dense regression coefficients) in Section 5.2: Sampling distributions of the moment estimators and the parameter estimators, over 500 Monte Carlos are displayed for the case of $n=5000$.

and those based on debiasing (Bellec, 2024; Celentano and Wainwright, 2023) is warranted in a future work: for instance, which estimator has better efficiency or which estimator performs better when $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$ is unknown or when sufficient conditions (e.g. Assumption $U$ ) for universality are violated with non-Gaussian designs. We end our article with the following discussion.

# 6.1 Statistical Inference 

A problem that is worth pursuing in future work relates to the potentially non-Gaussian limiting distribution. When $\|\boldsymbol{\beta}\|$ is small, the corresponding $U$-statistic estimator may have positive probability of being negative and the truncation used in (4) could lead to non-Gaussian limiting distributions of $\tilde{\gamma}_{\beta}^{2}$. It will be an interesting problem to investigate whether the bootstrap approach also delivers asymptotically valid inference in such a setting.

### 6.2 Unknown Population Covariance Matrix

In this paper, we mostly assume that $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$ is known, an assumption ubiquitously adopted in the current literature (see Section 1.2). Progress can be made when $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$ is unknown, but under specific conditions; see e.g. Section 3 and Appendix G. It will be of greater interest to examine the case if we weaken the assumptions on $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$ or $\mathbf{X}$ imposed in Section 3.

### 6.3 Single-Index Models (SIM) and Model Misspecification

Compared to GLMs, isotonic Single-Index Models (SIMs) offer a more flexible modeling option as they allow the link function to be unknown and nonparametric. To the best of our knowledge, Bellec (2024) is among the first to systematically study inference of functionals of regression coefficients in SIMs under proportional asymptotics. It is interesting to extend our framework to single-index models but it requires estimating the link function and hence higher-order moments, a complication that we plan to address in a separate paper. Another direction is to investigate if similar results for ATE still hold under the assumptions of Su et al. (2023), where only the propensity score is modeled by high-dimensional logistic regression but the outcome regression model is arbitrary. Finally, whenever parametric models such as GLMs are used, model misspecification is of potential concerns. The semiparametric partially nonlinear regression parameters considered in Vansteelandt and Dukes (2022), which reduce to functionals of regression coefficients when GLMs are correctly specified, can be another promising future avenue for our work.
