# A Preparatory Results 

Lemma 8 (First- and Second-Order Stein's lemma). For $\mathbf{Z} \sim \mathrm{N}_{p}(\mathbf{0}, \mathbf{I})$, we have for $f: \mathbb{R}^{p} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$ that is differentiable,

$$
\mathbb{E}[\mathbf{Z} f(\mathbf{Z})]=\mathbb{E}[\nabla f(\mathbf{Z})]
$$

Similarly, we have for $h: \mathbb{R}^{p} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$ and $f: \mathbb{R}^{p} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$ that are twice differentiable,

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathbb{E}\left[\left(\mathbf{Z} \mathbf{Z}^{\top}-\mathbf{I}\right) h(\mathbf{Z})\right] & =\mathbb{E}\left[\nabla^{2} h(\mathbf{Z})\right] \\
\mathbb{E}\left[\left(\mathbf{Z}^{\top} f(\mathbf{Z})-\operatorname{div} f(\mathbf{Z})\right)^{2}\right] & =\mathbb{E}\left[\|f(\mathbf{Z})\|^{2}+\operatorname{trace}\left(\nabla^{2} f(\mathbf{Z})\right)\right]
\end{aligned}
$$

Corollary 1. For $\mathbf{X} \sim \mathrm{N}_{p}(\boldsymbol{\mu}, \boldsymbol{\Sigma})$, we have, for $f: \mathbb{R}^{p} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$ that is differentiable,

$$
\mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X} f(\mathbf{X})]=\boldsymbol{\mu} \mathbb{E}[f(\mathbf{X})]+\boldsymbol{\Sigma} \mathbb{E}[\nabla f(\mathbf{X})]
$$

In addition, we have, for $\mathbf{f}: \mathbb{R}^{p} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^{p}$ that is coordinate-wisely differentiable,

$$
\mathbb{E}\left[\mathbf{X}^{\top} \mathbf{f}(\mathbf{X})\right]=\boldsymbol{\mu}^{\top} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{f}(\mathbf{X})]+\operatorname{trace}[\boldsymbol{\Sigma} \mathbb{E}[\nabla \mathbf{f}(\mathbf{X})]]
$$

Similarly, we have for $h: \mathbb{R}^{p} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$ that is twice differentiable,

$$
\mathbb{E}\left[\left(\mathbf{X} \mathbf{X}^{\top}-\boldsymbol{\Sigma}\right) h(\mathbf{X})\right]=\boldsymbol{\mu} \boldsymbol{\mu}^{\top} \mathbb{E}[h(\mathbf{X})]+\boldsymbol{\mu}(\boldsymbol{\Sigma} \mathbb{E}[\nabla h(\mathbf{X})])^{\top}+(\boldsymbol{\Sigma} \mathbb{E}[\nabla h(\mathbf{X})]) \boldsymbol{\mu}^{\top}+\boldsymbol{\Sigma} \mathbb{E}\left[\nabla^{2} h(\mathbf{X})\right] \boldsymbol{\Sigma}
$$

Proof. The proof for the first statement is trivial and hence omitted. Let $\mathbf{Z} \sim \mathrm{N}_{p}(\mathbf{0}, \mathbf{I})$ then $\mathbf{X} \stackrel{d}{=} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{1 / 2} \mathbf{Z}+\boldsymbol{\mu}$.

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \mathbb{E}\left[\left(\mathbf{X} \mathbf{X}^{\top}-\boldsymbol{\Sigma}\right) h(\mathbf{X})\right] \\
= & \mathbb{E}\left[\left((\mathbf{X}-\boldsymbol{\mu}+\boldsymbol{\mu})(\mathbf{X}-\boldsymbol{\mu}+\boldsymbol{\mu})^{\top}-\boldsymbol{\Sigma}\right) h(\mathbf{X})\right] \\
= & \boldsymbol{\mu} \boldsymbol{\mu}^{\top} \mathbb{E}[h(\mathbf{X})]+\boldsymbol{\mu} \mathbb{E}\left[(\mathbf{X}-\boldsymbol{\mu})^{\top} h(\mathbf{X})\right]+\mathbb{E}[(\mathbf{X}-\boldsymbol{\mu}) h(\mathbf{X})] \boldsymbol{\mu}^{\top}+\mathbb{E}\left[\left\{(\mathbf{X}-\boldsymbol{\mu})(\mathbf{X}-\boldsymbol{\mu})^{\top}-\boldsymbol{\Sigma}\right\} h(\mathbf{X})\right] \\
= & \boldsymbol{\mu} \boldsymbol{\mu}^{\top} \mathbb{E}[h(\mathbf{X})]+\boldsymbol{\mu}(\boldsymbol{\Sigma} \mathbb{E}[\nabla h(\mathbf{X})])^{\top}+(\boldsymbol{\Sigma} \mathbb{E}[\nabla h(\mathbf{X})]) \boldsymbol{\mu}^{\top}+\boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{1 / 2} \mathbb{E}\left[\left(\mathbf{Z} \mathbf{Z}^{\top}-\mathbf{I}\right) h\left(\boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{1 / 2} \mathbf{Z}+\boldsymbol{\mu}\right)\right] \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{1 / 2} \\
= & \boldsymbol{\mu} \boldsymbol{\mu}^{\top} \mathbb{E}[h(\mathbf{X})]+\boldsymbol{\mu}(\boldsymbol{\Sigma} \mathbb{E}[\nabla h(\mathbf{X})])^{\top}+(\boldsymbol{\Sigma} \mathbb{E}[\nabla h(\mathbf{X})]) \boldsymbol{\mu}^{\top}+\boldsymbol{\Sigma} \mathbb{E}\left[\nabla^{2} h(\mathbf{X})\right] \boldsymbol{\Sigma}
\end{aligned}
$$

Corollary 2. For $Z \sim \mathrm{~N}\left(\lambda, \gamma^{2}\right)$, given a twice-differentiable function $f: \mathbb{R} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$, we have

$$
\mathbb{E} f(Z)(Z-\lambda)^{2}=\gamma^{2} \mathbb{E} f(Z)+\left(\gamma^{2}\right)^{2} \mathbb{E} f^{\prime \prime}(Z)
$$

Proof. Repeatedly applying Lemma 8, we have

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathbb{E} f(Z)(Z-\lambda)^{2} & =\mathbb{E} f(Z)(Z-\lambda)(Z-\lambda) \\
& =\gamma^{2} \mathbb{E}\left\{f^{\prime}(Z)(Z-\lambda)+f(Z)\right\} \\
& =\gamma^{2} \mathbb{E} f(Z)+\left(\gamma^{2}\right)^{2} \mathbb{E} f^{\prime \prime}(Z)
\end{aligned}
$$

As our proposed MoM-based estimators critically rely on inverting a nonlinear map (generally without an analytic form), particularly in Appendix D, we also need the following result that is a consequence of the Inverse Function Theorem and a result believed to be due to Hadamard (Theorem 6.2.8 of Krantz and Parks (2002)).

Lemma 9 (Hadamard Global Inverse Function Theorem). Suppose $\mathcal{R}$ and $\mathcal{M}$ are smooth, simply connected open sets of $\mathbb{R}^{k}$ for some positive integer $k$ and $\Psi: \mathcal{R} \rightarrow \mathcal{M}$ is a twice-differentiable and proper map. If the Jacobian $\nabla \Psi$ has determinant bounded away from 0 over $\mathcal{R}$, then $\Psi$ is a diffeomorphism.

Proof. By Theorem 6.2.8 of Krantz and Parks (2002), since $\mathcal{R}$ and $\mathcal{M}$ are smooth, simply connected open sets of $\mathbb{R}^{k}$ and $\Psi$ is proper and has non-singular Jacobian, $\Psi$ is a homeomorphism and hence bijective. By the Inverse Function Theorem, since the Jacobian $\nabla \Psi$ has determinant bounded away from zero, $\Psi$ is a local diffeomorphism. A bijective map that is a local diffeomorphism is a (global) diffeomorphism.

Taking $x \in \mathcal{R} . \Psi$ is a proper map if $x \rightarrow \partial \mathcal{R}$ implies that $\Psi(x) \rightarrow \partial \mathcal{M}$ : see Definition 6.2.2 of Krantz and Parks (2002) and discussions thereafter.

# B Proof for the system of moment equations for GLM 

After the preparation in the previous section, we are ready to prove the first part of Lemma 3. We only need to verify (5c), (5d), and (5f) of (5).

Regarding (5c), we can simply apply Corollary 1 and obtain:

$$
\begin{aligned}
m_{\mathbf{X} Y, \mathbf{X}} & =\mathbb{E}\left[\phi\left(\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right) \mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X}]=\mathbb{E}\left[\phi\left(\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)\right] \boldsymbol{\mu}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \boldsymbol{\mu}+\mathbb{E}\left[\phi^{\prime}\left(\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)\right] \boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \boldsymbol{\mu} \\
& =\mathbb{E}[Y] \boldsymbol{\mu}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \boldsymbol{\mu}+\mathbb{E}\left[\phi^{\prime}\left(\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)\right] \boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\mu} \\
& =m_{Y} \cdot m_{\mathbf{X}, 2}+\mathrm{f}_{1}\left(\lambda_{\beta}, \gamma_{\beta}^{2}\right) \cdot \lambda_{\beta}
\end{aligned}
$$

The derivations of (5d) and (5f) follow the same strategy, hence omitted.

## C Derivations of the system of moment equations for the examples in Section 4

This section is devoted to deriving the system of moment equations for the three examples considered in Section 4.

## C. 1 Derivation of (11)

In this section, we derive the system of moment equations (11) in Lemma 5.
Derivation of (11). The system of moment equations in (11) follows directly from Corollary 1 and some elementary calculations. We only show the following three identities as the others are trivial:

1. Derivation related to $\mathbb{E}\left[A \mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X} A]$ :

$$
\mathbb{E}\left[A \mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X} A]
$$

$$
\begin{aligned}
& =\mathbb{E}\left[\phi\left(\boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right) \mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X} A] \\
& =\mathbb{E}[A] \boldsymbol{\mu}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X} A]+\mathbb{E}\left[\phi^{\prime}\left(\boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)\right] \boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X} A]
\end{aligned}
$$

2. Derivation related to $\mathbb{E}\left[Y \mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X} A]$ :

$$
\mathbb{E}\left[Y \mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X} A]=\psi \cdot \mathbb{E}\left[A \mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X} A]+\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X} A]
$$

3. Derivation related to $\mathbb{E}\left[Y A \mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X} A]$ :

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \mathbb{E}\left[Y A \mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X} A] \\
= & \psi \cdot \mathbb{E}\left[A \mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X} A]+\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \mathbb{E}\left[\mathbf{X} \mathbf{X}^{\top} A\right] \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X} A] \\
= & \psi \cdot m_{\mathbf{X} A, 2}+\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \mathbb{E}\left[\mathbf{X} \mathbf{X}^{\top} \phi\left(\boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)\right] \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X} A] \\
= & \psi \cdot m_{\mathbf{X} A, 2}+\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top}\left\{\begin{array}{c}
\boldsymbol{\Sigma} \mathbb{E}[A]+\boldsymbol{\mu} \boldsymbol{\mu}^{\top} \mathbb{E}[A]+\mathbb{E}\left[\phi^{\prime}\left(\boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)\right]\left(\boldsymbol{\mu} \boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}+\boldsymbol{\Sigma} \boldsymbol{\alpha} \boldsymbol{\mu}^{\top}\right) \\
+\mathbb{E}\left[\phi^{\prime \prime}\left(\boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)\right] \boldsymbol{\Sigma} \boldsymbol{\alpha} \boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}
\end{array}\right\} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X} A] \\
= & \psi \cdot m_{\mathbf{X} A, 2}+\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X} A] \mathbb{E}[A]+\lambda_{\beta} \mathbb{E}[A] \boldsymbol{\mu}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X} A] \\
& +\mathrm{f}_{1}\left(\lambda_{\alpha}, \gamma_{\alpha}^{2}\right)\left(\lambda_{\beta} \boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X} A]+\gamma_{\alpha, \beta} \boldsymbol{\mu}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X} A]\right)+\mathbb{E}\left[\phi^{\prime \prime}\left(\boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)\right] \gamma_{\alpha, \beta} \boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X} A]
\end{aligned}
$$

# C. 2 Derivation of (12) 

In this section, we derive the system of moment equations (12) in Lemma 6.
Derivation of (12). Again, the system of moment equations in (12) follows directly from Corollary 1 and some elementary calculation. We only show the following identities as the others are trivial.

1. Derivation related to $\mathbb{E}[A Y]$ :

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathbb{E}[A Y] & =\mathbb{E}\left[\eta\left(\boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right) \mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \boldsymbol{\beta} \\

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathbb{E}\left[A \mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \mathbf{v} & =\mathbb{E}\left[\eta\left(\boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right) \mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \mathbf{v}=\left(\mathbb{E}\left[\eta\left(\boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)\right] \boldsymbol{\mu}^{\top}+\mathbb{E}\left[\eta^{\prime}\left(\boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)\right] \boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}\right) \mathbf{v} \\

\mathbb{E}\left[A Y \mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \mathbf{v} & =\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \mathbb{E}\left[\mathbf{X} \mathbf{X}^{\top} \eta\left(\boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)\right] \mathbf{v} \\
& =\mathbb{E}\left[\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \mathbf{X} \eta\left(\boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right) \mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \mathbf{v} \\
& =\left(\mathbb{E}\left[\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \mathbf{X} \eta\left(\boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)\right] \boldsymbol{\mu}^{\top}+\mathbb{E}\left[\eta\left(\boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)\right] \boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}+\mathbb{E}\left[\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \mathbf{X} \eta^{\prime}\left(\boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)\right] \boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}\right) \mathbf{v} \\

\end{aligned}
$$

$$
\begin{aligned}
& +\mathbb{E}\left[\eta^{\prime}\left(\boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)\right] \boldsymbol{\mu}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\beta} \cdot \boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma} \mathbf{v}+\mathbb{E}\left[\eta^{\prime \prime}\left(\boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)\right] \boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma} \boldsymbol{\beta} \cdot \boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma} \mathbf{v} \\
= & \left\{m_{0} \cdot \boldsymbol{\mu}^{\top} \mathbf{v}+\mathbb{E}\left[\eta^{\prime}\left(\boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)\right] \cdot \boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma} \mathbf{v}\right\} \cdot \boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\mu}+m_{0} \cdot \boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma} \mathbf{v} \\

# C. 3 Derivation of (13) 

In this section, we derive the system of moment equations (13) in Lemma 7.
Derivation of (13). All the moment equations of (13) are equivalent to those given in Lemma 3 except the last one, which we now derive by again applying Corollary 1:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \mathbb{E}\left[A \mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X} Y] \\
= & \mathbb{E}\left[\eta\left(\boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right) \mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbb{E}\left[\mathbf{X} \phi\left(\mathbf{X}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\beta}\right)\right] \\
= & \left\{\mathbb{E}[A] \boldsymbol{\mu}^{\top}+\mathbb{E}\left[\eta^{\prime}\left(\boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)\right] \boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}\right\} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1}\left\{\boldsymbol{\mu} \mathbb{E}[Y]+\boldsymbol{\Sigma} \boldsymbol{\beta} \mathbb{E}\left[\phi^{\prime}\left(\mathbf{X}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\beta}\right)\right]\right\} \\
= & m_{A} \cdot m_{Y} \cdot m_{\mathbf{X}, 2}+m_{A} \cdot \mathrm{f}_{1}\left(\lambda_{\beta}, \gamma_{\beta}^{2}\right) \cdot \lambda_{\beta}+m_{Y} \cdot \mathrm{~g}_{1}\left(\lambda_{\alpha}, \gamma_{\alpha}^{2}\right) \cdot \lambda_{\alpha}+\mathrm{g}_{1}\left(\lambda_{\alpha}, \gamma_{\alpha}^{2}\right) \cdot \mathrm{f}_{1}\left(\lambda_{\beta}, \gamma_{\beta}^{2}\right) \cdot \gamma_{\alpha, \beta}
\end{aligned}
$$

## D Proofs Related to Identifications under Gaussian Designs
## D. 1 GLMs with non-zero covariate mean $\boldsymbol{\mu}$

In this section, we first prove Lemma 3, which states that the linear form $\lambda_{\beta}=\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\mu}$ and the quadratic form $\gamma_{\beta}^{2}=\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma} \boldsymbol{\beta}$ of the regression coefficient vector $\boldsymbol{\beta}$ in Model GLM are simultaneously identifiable from the system of (population) moment equations (5).

Proof of Lemma 3. Let $Z \sim \mathrm{~N}\left(\lambda_{\beta}, \gamma_{\beta}^{2}\right)$. Recall that we reduce the first four moment equations (5) as

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \mathrm{f}_{0}\left(\lambda_{\beta}, \gamma_{\beta}^{2}\right)-m_{1}=0 \\
& \gamma_{\beta}^{2} \mathrm{f}_{1}^{2}\left(\lambda_{\beta}, \gamma_{\beta}^{2}\right)-m_{2}=0
\end{aligned}
$$

and denote the forward map as $\Psi_{\mathrm{GLM}, \beta}$.
We first compute the Jacobian $\nabla \Psi_{\mathrm{GLM}, \beta}$ as

$$
\begin{aligned}
\nabla \Psi_{\mathrm{GLM}, \beta} & =\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\mathbb{E} \phi^{\prime}(Z) & 2 \mathbb{E} \phi^{\prime}(Z) \mathbb{E} \phi^{\prime}(Z)\left(Z-\lambda_{\beta}\right) \\
\frac{1}{2 \gamma_{\beta}^{2}} \mathbb{E} \phi^{\prime}(Z)\left(Z-\lambda_{\beta}\right) & \frac{1}{\gamma_{\beta}^{2}} \mathbb{E} \phi^{\prime}(Z) \mathbb{E} \phi^{\prime}(Z)\left(Z-\lambda_{\beta}\right)^{2}
\end{array}\right) \\
& =\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\mathbb{E} \phi^{\prime}(Z) & 2 \gamma_{\beta}^{2} \mathbb{E} \phi^{\prime}(Z) \mathbb{E} \phi^{\prime \prime}(Z) \\
\frac{1}{2} \mathbb{E} \phi^{\prime \prime}(Z) & \mathbb{E} \phi^{\prime}(Z)\left(\mathbb{E} \phi^{\prime}(Z)+\gamma_{\beta}^{2} \mathbb{E} \phi^{\prime \prime \prime}(Z)\right)
\end{array}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

Without loss of generality, we take the link function $\phi$ to be monotonically strictly increasing. The determinant of $\nabla \Psi_{\mathrm{GLM}, \beta}$ is

$$
\begin{aligned}
\left|\nabla \Psi_{\mathrm{GLM}, \beta}\right| & =\frac{1}{\gamma_{\beta}^{2}} \mathbb{E} \phi^{\prime}(Z)\left\{\mathbb{E} \phi^{\prime}(Z) \mathbb{E} \phi^{\prime}(Z)\left(Z-\lambda_{\beta}\right)^{2}-\left(\mathbb{E} \phi^{\prime}(Z)\left(Z-\lambda_{\beta}\right)\right)^{2}\right\} \\
& =\mathbb{E} \phi^{\prime}(Z)\left\{\mathbb{E}^{2} \phi^{\prime}(Z)+\gamma_{\beta}^{2}\left(\mathbb{E} \phi^{\prime}(Z) \mathbb{E} \phi^{\prime \prime \prime}(Z)-\mathbb{E}^{2} \phi^{\prime \prime}(Z)\right)\right\} \geq 0
\end{aligned}
$$

where $\left|\nabla \Psi_{\mathrm{GLM}, \beta}\right| \geq 0$ follows from applying Cauchy-Schwarz inequality to the first line of the above display and $\phi$ monotonically increasing. Here, we note that monotonicity is but a sufficient condition for the above inequality to hold - which leaves the door open to extend our approach to SIMs with general non-monotonic link functions.

Lemma 9 implies that we are only left to show that the above inequality is strict and the corresponding map $\Psi$ is proper. Suppose on the contrary, the above inequality is an equality. Then we have, with probability one,

$$
\sqrt{\phi^{\prime}(Z)}\left(Z-\lambda_{\beta}\right) \equiv \frac{\mathbb{E} \phi^{\prime}(Z)\left(Z-\lambda_{\beta}\right)}{\mathbb{E} \phi^{\prime}(Z)} \sqrt{\phi^{\prime}(Z)}
$$

which is equivalent to, with probability one,

$$
Z-\lambda_{\beta} \equiv \frac{\mathbb{E} \phi^{\prime}(Z)\left(Z-\lambda_{\beta}\right)}{\mathbb{E} \phi^{\prime}(Z)} \text { or } \sqrt{\phi^{\prime}(Z)} \equiv 0
$$

a contradiction unless $Z$ is degenerate (i.e. $\gamma_{\beta}^{2}=0$ ). Thus we have proved that the forward map $\Psi_{\mathrm{GLM}, \beta}$ is a local diffeomorphism. $\Psi_{\mathrm{GLM}, \beta}$ is also proper under Assumption L.

In fact, for linear and log-linear link functions, it is easy to see that $|\nabla \Psi|$ is strictly positive for strictly bounded $\lambda_{\beta}$ and $\gamma_{\beta}^{2}$. For probit link, we observe that

$$
\begin{aligned}
\left|\nabla \Psi_{\mathrm{GLM}, \beta}\right| & =\mathbb{E} \phi^{\prime}(Z)\left\{\mathbb{E}^{2} \phi^{\prime}(Z)+\gamma_{\beta}^{2}\left(\mathbb{E} \phi^{\prime}(Z) \mathbb{E} \phi^{\prime \prime \prime}(Z)-\mathbb{E}^{2} \phi^{\prime \prime}(Z)\right)\right\} \\
& =\frac{1}{\left(2 \pi\left(1+\gamma_{\beta}^{2}\right)\right)^{3 / 2}} \exp \left\{-\frac{3 \lambda_{\beta}^{2}}{2\left(1+\gamma_{\beta}^{2}\right)}\right\}\left(1+\gamma_{\beta}^{2}\left\{\frac{\lambda_{\beta}^{2}}{\left(1+\gamma_{\beta}^{2}\right)^{2}}-\frac{1}{1+\gamma_{\beta}^{2}}-\frac{\lambda_{\beta}^{2}}{\left(1+\gamma_{\beta}^{2}\right)^{2}}\right\}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

$$
=\frac{1}{\left(2 \pi\left(1+\gamma_{\beta}^{2}\right)\right)^{3 / 2}} \exp \left\{-\frac{3 \lambda_{\beta}^{2}}{2\left(1+\gamma_{\beta}^{2}\right)}\right\} \frac{1}{1+\gamma_{\beta}^{2}}>0
$$

if $\lambda_{\beta}^{2}$ and $\gamma_{\beta}^{2}$ are strictly bounded.
For logit link, there is no analytic expression for $\left|\nabla \Psi_{\mathrm{GLM}, \beta}\right|$ but it is easy to numerically show that $\left|\nabla \Psi_{\mathrm{GLM}, \beta}\right|$ is strictly larger than zero, and hence $\Psi_{\mathrm{GLM}, \beta}$ is a diffeomorphism. The remaining part of Lemma 3 is straightforward to prove and hence omitted.

## E Proofs Related to CAN
## E. 1 General results for limiting distributions of moment estimators

We first state a general result. Consider the following pair of random variables, comprised of a first-order and a second-order degenerate $U$-statistic:

$$
\left(\sum_{i=1}^{n} g_{n}\left(O_{i}\right) \sum_{1 \leq i_{1}<i_{2} \leq n} h_{n}\left(O_{i_{1}}, O_{i_{2}}\right)\right)^{\top}
$$

with $\mathbb{E} g_{n}(O)=0$ and $\mathbb{E} h_{n}(O, o)=0$ almost surely. Our goal is to establish their joint limiting distribution as the sample size $n$ approaches infinity.

The following result in Bhattacharya and Ghosh (1992) provides a set of generic sufficient conditions under which (16) has a Gaussian limit.

Lemma 10 (Corollary 1.4 of Bhattacharya and Ghosh (1992)). Suppose that the following conditions hold: as $n \rightarrow \infty$,
(1) $n \mathbb{E} g_{n}(O)^{2} \rightarrow \sigma_{g}^{2}$

(2) $n^{2} \mathbb{E} h_{n}\left(O_{1}, O_{2}\right)^{2} \rightarrow \sigma_{h}^{2}$;
(3) $n \mathbb{E} g_{n}(O)^{4} \rightarrow 0$;
(4) $n^{3} \mathbb{E}\left(\int_{o} h_{n}(O, o)^{2} \mathrm{~d} \mathbb{P}(o)\right)^{2} \rightarrow 0$;
(5) $n^{4} \mathbb{E}\left(\int_{o} h_{n}\left(O_{1}, o\right) h_{n}\left(O_{2}, o\right) \mathrm{d} \mathbb{P}(o)\right)^{2} \rightarrow 0$;
(6) $n^{2} \mathbb{E} h_{n}\left(O_{1}, O_{2}\right)^{4} \rightarrow 0$;
(7) $n^{3} \mathbb{E}\left(\int_{o} g_{n}(o) h_{n}(O, o) \mathrm{d} \mathbb{P}(o)\right)^{2} \rightarrow 0$.

We then have

$$
\left(\sum_{i=1}^{n} g_{n}\left(O_{i}\right)\right. \underset{\sum_{1 \leq i_{1} \neq i_{2} \leq n}}{\sum_{i} h_{n}\left(O_{i_{1}}, O_{i_{2}}\right)} \xrightarrow{\mathcal{E}} \mathrm{N}_{2}\left(\binom{0}{0},\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\sigma_{g}^{2} & 0 \\
0 & \sigma_{h}^{2} / 2
\end{array}\right)\right)
$$

Let $\mathcal{O} \ni O:=(\mathbf{X}, W)$ where $\mathbf{X} \in \mathbb{R}^{p}$ and $W \in \mathcal{W}$. In the sequel, we assume that there exist two functions $f, g: \mathcal{W} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$ of $W$. & +\operatorname{trace}\left[\boldsymbol{\Sigma} \mathbb{M} \boldsymbol{\Sigma} \mathbb{E}\left[\nabla^{2} \nu_{f}^{2}(\mathbf{X})\right]\right] \mathbb{E}\left[g(W)^{2}\right]+\operatorname{trace}\left[\boldsymbol{\Sigma} \mathbb{M} \boldsymbol{\Sigma} \mathbb{E}\left[\nabla^{2} \nu_{g}^{2}(\mathbf{X})\right]\right] \mathbb{E}\left[f(W)^{2}\right] .
\end{aligned}
$$

By symmetry,

$$
\begin{aligned}
J_{2}= & O(1)+\operatorname{trace}\left[\boldsymbol{\Sigma} \mathbb{M} \boldsymbol{\Sigma} \mathbb{M}\right] \mathbb{E}^{2}\left[f(W) g(W)\right]+\operatorname{trace}\left[\left(\boldsymbol{\Sigma} \mathbb{M} \boldsymbol{\Sigma} \mathbb{E}\left[\nabla^{2} \nu_{g}^{2}(\mathbf{X})\right]\right)^{2}\right] \\
& +2 \operatorname{trace}\left[\boldsymbol{\Sigma} \mathbb{M} \boldsymbol{\Sigma} \mathbb{M} \boldsymbol{\Sigma} \mathbb{E}\left[\nabla^{2} \nu_{g}^{2}(\mathbf{X})\right]\right] \mathbb{E}[f(W) g(W)]
\end{aligned}
$$

Finally, $J_{3}=O(1)$ is the same as $I_{0}$.
Conditions (3) - (7) only concern rates instead of actual convergence to a particular (non-trivial) limit and under our conditions, they are all satisfied. We start by checking Conditions (3) \& (6). For (3), we need to show the following terms vanishing to 0 :

$$
n \frac{1}{n^{2}} \mathbb{E}\left\{f(W) \mathbf{X}^{\top} \mathbb{M} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X} g(W)]\right\}^{4}
$$

$$
\begin{aligned}
& =\frac{1}{n} \mathbb{E}\left\{\eta_{f}(\mathbf{X})\left(\mathbf{X}^{\top} \mathbb{M} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X} g(W)]\right)^{4}\right\} \\
& \leq \frac{1}{n} \mathbb{E}^{1 / 2} \eta_{f}(\mathbf{X})^{2} \mathbb{E}^{1 / 2}\left(\mathbf{X}^{\top} \mathbb{M} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X} g(W)]\right)^{8} \leq \frac{1}{n} \rightarrow 0

where the last inequality follows from Lemma 12. By symmetry, we also have

n \frac{1}{n^{2}} \mathbb{E}\left\{g(W) \mathbf{X}^{\top} \mathbb{M} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X} f(W)]\right\}^{4} \rightarrow 0

$$

where the last inequality follows from Lemma 12.

& +C \mathbb{E}\left\{\mathbf{X}_{2}^{\top} \mathbb{M} \nabla^{2} \eta_{f}\left(\mathbf{X}_{1}\right) \mathbb{M} \mathbf{X}_{2} \eta_{g}\left(\mathbf{X}_{2}\right)\left\{\mathbf{X}_{1}^{\top} \mathbb{M} \mathbf{X}_{2}\right\}^{2}\right\} \\
= & C \mathbb{E}\left\{\eta_{g}\left(\mathbf{X}_{2}\right) \mathbf{X}_{2}^{\top} \mathbb{M}^{2} \mathbf{X}_{2} \mathbf{X}_{2}^{\top} \mathbb{M} \mathbb{E}\left[\nabla^{2} \eta_{f}\left(\mathbf{X}_{1}\right)\right] \mathbb{M} \mathbf{X}_{2}\right\}+C \mathbb{E}\left\{\mathbf{X}_{2}^{\top} \mathbb{M} \mathbf{X}_{2} \eta_{g}\left(\mathbf{X}_{2}\right) \mathbf{X}_{2}^{\top} \mathbb{M} \mathbb{E}\left[\nabla^{2} \eta_{f}\left(\mathbf{X}_{1}\right)\right] \mathbb{M} \mathbf{X}_{2}\right\} \\
& +C \mathbb{E}\left\{\mathbf{X}_{2}^{\top} \mathbb{M} \nabla^{2} \eta_{f}\left(\mathbf{X}_{1}\right) \mathbb{M} \mathbf{X}_{2} \eta_{g}\left(\mathbf{X}_{2}\right)\left\{\mathbf{X}_{1}^{\top} \mathbb{M} \mathbf{X}_{2}\right\}^{2}\right\} \lesssim p^{3}

# E. 2 Linear and Quadratic Forms of GLMs 

The key step is to simplify $\mathbb{E}[\nabla \mu(\mathbf{X})], \mathbb{E}\left[\nabla \nu^{2}(\mathbf{X})\right]$ and $\mathbb{E}\left[\nabla^{2} \nu^{2}(\mathbf{X})\right]$; note that here we have considered the joint convergence of the $U$-statistic-based estimators of the involved moments in (5) using the Cramér-Wold device. To this end, we have

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathbb{E}[\nabla \mu(\mathbf{X})] & =\mathbb{E}\left[\nabla \phi\left(\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)\right]=\mathbb{E}\left[\phi^{\prime}\left(\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)\right] \mathbf{X} \\
& =\mathbb{E}\left[\phi^{\prime}\left(\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)\right] \boldsymbol{\mu}+\mathbb{E}\left[\phi^{\prime}\left(\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)\right] \boldsymbol{\Sigma} \boldsymbol{\beta} \\
& =(\boldsymbol{\mu}+\boldsymbol{\Sigma} \boldsymbol{\beta}) \mathbb{E}\left[\mu^{\prime}(\mathbf{X})\right] \\
\mathbb{E}\left[\nabla \nu^{2}(\mathbf{X})\right] & =\mathbb{E}\left[\nabla\left\{\phi^{2}\left(\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)+\sigma^{2}\left(\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)\right\}\right] \\
& =\left\{\mathbb{E}\left[\phi^{2 \prime}\left(\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)\right]+\mathbb{E}\left[\sigma^{2 \prime}\left(\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)\right]\right\} \cdot(\boldsymbol{\mu}+\boldsymbol{\Sigma} \boldsymbol{\beta}) \\
& =(\boldsymbol{\mu}+\boldsymbol{\Sigma} \boldsymbol{\beta}) \mathbb{E}\left[\nu^{2 \prime}(\mathbf{X})\right] \\
\mathbb{E}\left[\nabla^{2} \nu^{2}(\mathbf{X})\right] & =\mathbb{E}\left[\nabla^{2}\left\{\phi^{2}\left(\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)+\sigma^{2}\left(\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)\right\}\right] \\
& =(\boldsymbol{\mu}+\boldsymbol{\Sigma} \boldsymbol{\beta})\left\{\mathbb{E}\left[\nabla \phi^{2 \prime}\left(\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)\right]+\mathbb{E}\left[\nabla \sigma^{2 \prime}\left(\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)\right]\right\} \\
& =(\boldsymbol{\mu}+\boldsymbol{\Sigma} \boldsymbol{\beta})(\boldsymbol{\mu}+\boldsymbol{\Sigma} \boldsymbol{\beta})^{\top}\left\{\mathbb{E}\left[\phi^{2 \prime \prime}\left(\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)\right]+\mathbb{E}\left[\sigma^{2 \prime \prime}\left(\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)\right]\right\} \\
& =(\boldsymbol{\mu}+\boldsymbol{\Sigma} \boldsymbol{\beta})(\boldsymbol{\mu}+\boldsymbol{\Sigma} \boldsymbol{\beta})^{\top}\left\{\mathbb{E}\left[\nu^{2 \prime \prime}(\mathbf{X})\right]\right\}
\end{aligned}
$$

Checking Condition 21, we need the following terms to converge to certain limits or $o(1)$ :

$$
\boldsymbol{\mu}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \boldsymbol{\mu}, \boldsymbol{\mu}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\mu}, \boldsymbol{\mu}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\beta}, \boldsymbol{\mu}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma} \boldsymbol{\beta}, \boldsymbol{\mu}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{2} \boldsymbol{\beta}, \boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma} \boldsymbol{\beta}, \boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{3} \boldsymbol{\beta}
$$

Checking Condition 22, we need the following terms to converge to certain limits:

$$
\boldsymbol{\mu}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\beta}, \boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma} \boldsymbol{\beta}
$$

When $\boldsymbol{\mu}=\mathbf{0}$, the above conditions reduce to $\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma} \boldsymbol{\beta}$ and/or $\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{3} \boldsymbol{\beta}$ converge to a limit.
We then need to check (20). Under Assumptions B and V, both requirements in (20) hold due to GLM and boundedness of $\|\boldsymbol{\beta}\|$.

# E. 3 Causal Effects in Linear Structural Equation Models 

For the causal effect estimation problem in Section 4.1,

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathbb{E}[A Y \mid \mathbf{X}] & =\mathbb{E}[A \mathbb{E}[Y \mid \mathbf{X}, A]]=\mathbb{E}\left[A \boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \mathbf{X}+\psi \cdot A \mid \mathbf{X}\right] \\
& =\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \mathbf{X} \cdot \eta\left(\boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)+\psi \cdot \eta\left(\boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

which is a function of $\left(\boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \mathbf{X}, \boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)$. Thus we only need to replace $\boldsymbol{\beta}$ 's in Appendix E. 2 by $\boldsymbol{\alpha}$ or a mix of $\boldsymbol{\alpha}$ and $\boldsymbol{\beta}$.

## E. 4 Mean Estimation under MAR

For the problem of mean estimation under MAR in Section 4.2, we only need to additionally consider to replace $\boldsymbol{\beta}$ 's in Appendix E. 2 by $\boldsymbol{\alpha}$ or a mix of $\boldsymbol{\alpha}$ and $\boldsymbol{\beta}$. The derivation is hence omitted.

## E. 5 Generalized Covariance Measure

For the problem of estimating GCM in Section 4.3, as we indicate after Theorem 5, we only need to introduce additional terms that involve the inner product between $\boldsymbol{\theta}^{\top} f(\boldsymbol{\Sigma})$ and $\boldsymbol{\alpha}, \boldsymbol{\beta}$ or $\boldsymbol{\mu}$ where $f$ is either the linear, the quadratic or the cubic function.

## F Proof Related to Universality

To extend the results from Gaussian designs to non-Gaussian designs, the following lemma from Chatterjee (2006) (also see Han and Shen (2023)) is pivotal.

Lemma 13. Let $\mathbf{X}:=\left(X_{1}, \cdots, X_{p}\right)^{\top}$ and $\mathbf{Z}:=\left(Z_{1}, \cdots, Z_{p}\right)^{\top}$ be two collections of random vectors with independent coordinates and matching first and second moments: $\mathbb{E}\left[X_{j}^{k}\right]=\mathbb{E}\left[Z_{j}^{k}\right]$ for $j=1, \cdots, p$ and $k \in\{1,2\}$. For any three-time differentiable function $f$,

$$
|\mathbb{E} f(\mathbf{X})-\mathbb{E} f(\mathbf{Z})| \leq \sum_{j=1}^{p} \max _{W_{j} \in\left\{X_{j}, Z_{j}\right\}}\left|\mathbb{E} \int_{0}^{W_{j}} \partial_{j}^{3} f\left(X_{1}, \cdots, X_{j-1}, t, Z_{j+1}, \cdots, Z_{p}\right)\left(W_{j}-t\right)^{2} \mathrm{~d} t\right|
$$

where $\partial_{j}^{3} f$ denotes the third-derivative of $f$ with respect to the $j$-th argument.
Lemma 14. Suppose that Assumptions L and U hold and M is a n.n.s.d. matrix such that $M^{-1} \leq$ $\lambda_{\min }(\mathbb{M}) \leq \lambda_{\max }(\mathbb{M}) \leq M$. Let $\mathbf{Z}$ be the corresponding Gaussian vector with the same first and second moments as $\mathbf{X}$. We then have the following assertions:

1. $\mathbb{E}\left(\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \mathbf{X} \phi\left(\boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)\right)=\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma} \boldsymbol{\alpha} \mathbb{E}\left[\phi^{\prime}\left(\mathbf{Z}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\alpha}\right)\right]+\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\mu} \mathbb{E}\left[\phi\left(\mathbf{Z}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\alpha}\right)\right]+O\left(p^{-3 / 4}\right)$;
2. $\mathbb{E}\left[\phi\left(\boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)\right]=\mathbb{E}\left[\phi\left(\boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \mathbf{Z}\right)\right]+O\left(p^{-3 / 4}\right)$;
3. $\mathbb{E}\left[\eta\left(\boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right) \mathbf{X}^{\top} \mathbb{M} \mathbb{E}\left[\phi\left(\mathbf{X}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\beta}\right) \mathbf{X} \mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \mathbb{M} \mathbf{X}\right]$;
4. $\left\{Y_{i}, \mathbf{X}_{i}\right\}_{i=1}^{n} \xrightarrow{\text { i.i.d. }} \mathbb{P}$ with $\mathbb{E}[Y \mid \mathbf{X}]=\phi\left(\boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)$ and let $T_{n}=\mathbb{U}_{n, 2}\left(Y_{1} \mathbf{X}_{1}^{\top} \mathbb{M} \mathbf{X}_{2} Y_{2}\right)$. Then $\operatorname{var}\left(T_{n}\right)=$ $O\left(1 / n+p / n^{2}\right)$ if $\mathbb{E}\left[\sigma^{4}(\mathbf{X})\right]<\infty$ with $\sigma^{2}(\mathbf{X})=\operatorname{var}(Y \mid \mathbf{X})$.

Proof. We prove assertion 1 and the proof of 2 follows by parallel arguments with obvious modifications. To prove 1, we first start with the case $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}=\mathbf{I}$ and $\boldsymbol{\mu}=\mathbf{0}$ and subsequently provide the details necessary for extending to the general mean and covariance cases. To this end define the function $f: \mathbb{R}^{p} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$ as $f(\boldsymbol{\omega})=\boldsymbol{\omega}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\beta} \phi\left(\boldsymbol{\omega}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\alpha}\right)$ for $\boldsymbol{\omega}=\left(\omega, \ldots, \omega_{p}\right)^{\top} \in \mathbb{R}^{p}$. Therefore it is clear that

$$
\frac{\partial^{3}}{\partial \omega_{j}^{3}} f(\boldsymbol{\omega})=\boldsymbol{\omega}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\beta} \alpha_{j}^{3} \phi^{(3)}\left(\boldsymbol{\omega}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\alpha}\right)+3 \beta_{j} \alpha_{j}^{2} \phi^{(2)}\left(\boldsymbol{\omega}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\alpha}\right)
$$

Therefore by Lemma 13

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \left|\mathbb{E}\left(\mathbf{X}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\beta} \phi\left(\mathbf{X}^{\top} \alpha\right)\right)-\mathbb{E}\left(\mathbf{Y}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\beta} \phi\left(\mathbf{Y}^{\top} \alpha\right)\right)\right| \\
& \leq \sum_{j=1}^{p} \max _{V_{j} \in\left\{X_{j}, Y_{j}\right\}}\left|\mathbb{E} \int_{0}^{V_{j}} \frac{\partial^{3}}{\partial \omega_{j}^{3}} f\left(X_{1}, \ldots, X_{j-1}, t, Y_{j+1}, \ldots, Y_{p}\right)\left(Z_{j}-t\right)^{2} d t\right| \\
& \leq T_{1}+T_{2}
\end{aligned}
$$

where $T_{1}, T_{2}$ respect the decomposition of $\frac{\partial^{3}}{\partial \omega_{j}^{3}} f(\boldsymbol{\omega})$ after applying triangle inequality to the display above. We first consider $T_{1}$ as follows by defining $W_{l, j}(\kappa, t)=\kappa\left(X_{l} \mathbb{1}(l<j)+Y_{l} \mathbb{1}(l>j)+t \mathbb{1}(l=j)\right)$

$$
T_{1}=\sum_{j=1}^{p}\left|\alpha_{j}^{3}\right| \max _{V_{j} \in\left\{X_{j}, Y_{j}\right\}}\left|\mathbb{E} \int_{0}^{V_{j}} \sum_{l=1}^{p} W_{l, j}\left(\beta_{l}, t\right) \phi^{(3)}\left(\sum_{l=1}^{p} W_{l, j}\left(\alpha_{l}, t\right)\right)\left(V_{j}-t\right)^{2} \mathrm{~d} t\right|
$$

Now by Cauchy-Schwarz inequality,

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \left|\mathbb{E} \int_{0}^{V_{j}} \sum_{l \neq j} W_{l, j}\left(\beta_{l}, t\right) \phi^{(3)}\left(\sum_{l=1}^{p} W_{l, j}\left(\alpha_{l}, t\right)\right)\left(V_{j}-t\right)^{2} \mathrm{~d} t\right| \\
& \leq\left(\left|\mathbb{E} \int_{0}^{V_{j}}\left\{\phi^{(3)}\left(\sum_{l=1}^{p} W_{l, j}\left(\alpha_{l}, t\right)\right)\right\}^{2} \mathrm{~d} t\right|\right)^{1 / 2}\left(\left|\mathbb{E} \int_{0}^{V_{j}}\left\{\sum_{l \neq j} W_{l, j}\left(\beta_{l}, t\right)\left(V_{j}-t\right)^{2}\right\}^{2} \mathrm{~d} t\right|\right)^{1 / 2}
\end{aligned}
$$

We analyze the two terms of the product in the last display as follows.

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \left|\mathbb{E} \int_{0}^{V_{j}}\left\{\phi^{(3)}\left(\sum_{l=1}^{p} W_{l, j}\left(\alpha_{l}, t\right)\right)\right\}^{2} \mathrm{~d} t\right| \\
& \leq\left|\mathbb{E} \int_{0}^{V_{j}}\left\{\phi^{(3)}\left(\sum_{l \neq j}^{p} W_{l, j}\left(\alpha_{l}, 0\right)\right)\right\}^{2} \mathrm{~d} t\right|+\left|\alpha_{j}\right|\left|\mathbb{E} \int_{0}^{V_{j}} t f_{\phi}\left(\sum_{l \neq j}^{p} W_{l, j}\left(\alpha_{l}, 0\right)+\alpha_{j} \chi(t)\right) \mathrm{d} t\right| \\
& =\left|\alpha_{j}\right|\left|\mathbb{E} \int_{0}^{V_{j}} t f_{\phi}\left(\sum_{l \neq j}^{p} W_{l, j}\left(\alpha_{l}, 0\right)+\alpha_{j} \chi(t)\right) \mathrm{d} t\right|
\end{aligned}
$$

where $\chi(t)$ is a $\sum_{l \neq j}^{p} W_{l, j}\left(\alpha_{l}, 0\right)$-measurable quantity between $\sum_{l \neq j}^{p} W_{l, j}\left(\alpha_{l}, 0\right)$ and $t$ by the exact form of Taylor remainder theorem, and we used the facts that $W_{l, j}(\kappa, t)=W_{l, j}(\kappa, 0)$ for $l \neq j$, $\mathbb{E}\left(V_{j}\right)=0$ and $V_{j} \Perp \sum_{l \neq j} W_{l, j}\left(\alpha_{l}, 0\right)$, and also the short-hand notation $f_{\phi}(\cdot):=\left\{\phi^{(3)}(\cdot)^{2}\right\}^{\prime}$. Now note that by the property of the function $\phi$ and the range of integration over $t$,

$$
\left|\mathbb{E} \int_{0}^{V_{j}} t f_{\phi}\left(\sum_{l \neq j}^{p} W_{l, j}\left(\alpha_{l}, 0\right)+\alpha_{j} \chi(t)\right) \mathrm{d} t\right|
$$

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \leq 2\left|\mathbb{E} \int_{0}^{V_{j}}\right| t \mid \exp \left\{2\left(\sum_{l \neq j}^{p} W_{l, j}\left(\alpha_{l}, 0\right)+\alpha_{j} \chi(t)\right)^{2} f\left(\sum_{l \neq j}^{p} W_{l, j}\left(\alpha_{l}, 0\right)+\alpha_{j} \chi(t)\right)\right\} \mathrm{d} t \mid \\
& \leq 2\left|\mathbb{E} \int_{0}^{V_{j}}\right| V_{j} \mid \exp \left\{2\left(\sum_{l \neq j}^{p} W_{l, j}\left(\alpha_{l}, 0\right)+\alpha_{j} \chi(t)\right)^{2} f\left(\sum_{l \neq j}^{p} W_{l, j}\left(\alpha_{l}, 0\right)+\alpha_{j} \chi(t)\right)\right\} \mathrm{d} t \mid
\end{aligned}
$$

Next, we again note that by the exact form of Taylor remainder theorem it is clear that $\chi(t)$ is $\sum_{l \neq j}^{p} W_{l, j}\left(\alpha_{l}, 0\right)$-measurable and hence

$$
\exp \left\{2\left(\sum_{l \neq j}^{p} W_{l, j}\left(\alpha_{l}, 0\right)+\alpha_{j} \chi(t)\right)^{2} f\left(\sum_{l \neq j}^{p} W_{l, j}\left(\alpha_{l}, 0\right)+\alpha_{j} \chi(t)\right)\right\} \pm V_{j}
$$

Now by direct calculations and the fact that $\max _{l=1}^{p}\left\|V_{l}\right\|_{\psi_{2}} \leq M,|\chi(t)| \leq\left|V_{j}\right|$ and $\lim _{|x| \rightarrow \infty} f(x)=$ 0 it is straightforward to verify that

$$
2\left|\mathbb{E} \int_{0}^{V_{j}}\right| V_{j} \mid \exp \left\{2\left(\sum_{l \neq j}^{p} W_{l, j}\left(\alpha_{l}, 0\right)+\alpha_{j} \chi(t)\right)^{2} f\left(\sum_{l \neq j}^{p} W_{l, j}\left(\alpha_{l}, 0\right)+\alpha_{j} \chi(t)\right)\right\} \mathrm{d} t \mid
$$

is bounded. Similarly using the fact that $\left\|\sum_{l \neq j} W_{l, j}\left(\beta_{l}, t\right)\right\|_{\psi_{2}} \leq M$ and it is independent of $V_{j}$ which also has $\psi_{2}$-norm bounded by $M$ one has by straightforward algebra that

$$
\left|\int_{0}^{V_{j}} \mathbb{E}\left\{\sum_{l \neq j} W_{l, j}\left(\beta_{l}, t\right)\left(V_{j}-t\right)^{2}\right\}^{2} \mathrm{~d} t\right|
$$

is bounded as well. Consequently there exists a constant $C(M)$ depending on $M$ such that

$$
\left|\mathbb{E} \int_{0}^{V_{j}} \sum_{l \neq j} W_{l, j}\left(\beta_{l}, t\right) \phi^{(3)}\left(\sum_{l=1}^{p} W_{l, j}\left(\alpha_{l}, t\right)\right)\left(V_{j}-t\right)^{2} \mathrm{~d} t\right| \leq C(M)\left|\alpha_{j}\right|
$$

Therefore for some constant $C^{\prime}(M)$ depending on $M$

$$
T_{1} \leq C^{\prime}(M) \sum_{j=1}^{p}\left|\alpha_{j}\right|^{7 / 2}=O\left(p^{-3 / 4}\right)
$$

By a parallel argument, it is easy to show that for some constant $C^{\prime \prime}(M)$ depending on $M$

$$
T_{2} \leq C^{\prime \prime}(M) \sum_{j=1}^{p}\left|\beta_{j}\right|\left|\alpha_{j}\right|^{5 / 2}=O\left(p^{-3 / 4}\right)
$$

This completes the proof of the first statement. The second statement follows directly from the same proof strategy and is thus omitted. It is noteworthy that if $\mathbb{E}\left[V_{j}\right]=\mu_{j}$ is not necessarily 0 when $\boldsymbol{\mu} \neq \mathbf{0}$, we can still apply the same arguments by further controlling the first term on the LHS

of (24) by leveraging the assumption on $\boldsymbol{\mu}$ imposed in Assumption D. When $\boldsymbol{\Sigma} \neq \mathbf{I}$, the above proof also goes through by renaming $\boldsymbol{\alpha}$ and $\boldsymbol{\beta}$ as $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{1 / 2} \boldsymbol{\alpha}$ and $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{1 / 2} \boldsymbol{\beta}$.

Finally, we prove the last claim that, for $T_{n}=\mathbb{U}_{n, 2}\left(Y_{1} \mathbf{X}_{1}^{\top} \mathbb{M} \mathbf{X}_{2} Y_{2}\right), \operatorname{var}\left(T_{n}\right)=O\left(1 / n+p / n^{2}\right)$ when $\mathbf{X}=\boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{1 / 2} \mathbf{Z}+\boldsymbol{\mu}$. We note that by Assumption D it is enough to consider the case $\boldsymbol{\mu}=\mathbf{0}$, which we assume henceforth. Thereafter, let $T_{1 n}$ and $T_{2 n}$ denote the first and second order term of the Hoeffding decomposition of $T_{n}$. Note that the flavor of this claim is different from the previous ones, as it is not about approximating the results that hold exactly under Gaussianity by Stein's lemma. We first show that $\operatorname{var}\left(T_{1 n}\right)=O(1 / n)$. To show this, note that with $v_{\mathbb{M}}:=\mathbb{M} \mathbb{E}(\mathbf{X} Y)=\mathbb{M} \mathbb{E}\left(\mathbf{X} \phi\left(\mathbf{X}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\beta}\right)\right)$ we have that

$$
\begin{aligned}
\operatorname{var}\left(T_{1 n}\right) & =\frac{1}{n} \operatorname{var}\left(Y \mathbf{X}^{\top} v_{\mathbb{M}}\right) \\
& =\frac{1}{n} \operatorname{var}\left(\phi\left(\mathbf{X}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\beta}\right) \mathbf{X}^{\top} v_{\mathbb{M}}\right)+\frac{1}{n} \mathbb{E}\left(\sigma^{2}(\mathbf{X})\left(v_{\mathbb{M}}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)^{2}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

Now since $\left\|v_{\mathbb{M}}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right\|_{\psi_{2}} \leq M\left\|v_{\mathbb{M}}\right\|_{2},\left\|v_{\mathbb{M}}\right\|_{2}^{2} \leq \lambda_{\max }^{2}(\mathbb{M})\left\|\mathbb{E}\left(\mathbf{X}^{\top} \phi\left(\mathbf{X}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\beta}\right)\right)\right\|_{2}^{2}$. But $\mathbf{X}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbb{E}\left(\mathbf{X} \phi\left(\mathbf{X}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\beta}\right)\right)=$ $\operatorname{Proj}_{L_{2}(\mathbb{P})}\left(\phi\left(\mathbf{X}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\beta}\right) \mid V\right)$ where $V=\operatorname{Span}(\mathbf{X})$. Therefore by the length contraction property of projection, we have

$$
\left\|\mathbf{X}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbb{E}\left(\mathbf{X} \phi\left(\mathbf{X}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\beta}\right)\right)\right\|_{L_{2}(\mathbb{P})}^{2} \leq\left\|\phi\left(\mathbf{X}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\beta}\right)\right\|_{L_{2}(\mathbb{P})}^{2}
$$

However,

$$
\begin{aligned}
\left\|\mathbf{X}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbb{E}\left(\mathbf{X} \phi\left(\mathbf{X}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\beta}\right)\right)\right\|_{L_{2}(\mathbb{P})}^{2} & =\mathbb{E}\left(\mathbf{X}^{\top} \phi\left(\mathbf{X}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\beta}\right)\right) \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbb{E}\left(\mathbf{X} \phi\left(\mathbf{X}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\beta}\right)\right) \\
& \geq \lambda_{\max }^{-1}(\boldsymbol{\Sigma})\left\|\mathbb{E}\left(\mathbf{X} \phi\left(\mathbf{X}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\beta}\right)\right)\right\|_{2}^{2}
\end{aligned}
$$

Therefore

$$
\left\|v_{\mathbb{M}}\right\|_{2}^{2} \leq \lambda_{\max }^{2}(\mathbb{M})\left\|\mathbb{E}\left(\mathbf{X}^{\top} \phi\left(\mathbf{X}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\beta}\right)\right)\right\|_{2}^{2} \leq \lambda_{\max }(\boldsymbol{\Sigma}) \lambda_{\max }(\mathbb{M})\left\|\phi\left(\mathbf{X}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\beta}\right)\right\|_{L_{2}(\mathbb{P})}^{2}<\infty
$$

Thus we have

$$
\begin{aligned}
\operatorname{var}\left(\phi\left(\mathbf{X}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\beta}\right) \mathbf{X}^{\top} v_{\mathbb{M}}\right) & \leq \mathbb{E}^{1 / 2}\left(\phi^{4}\left(\mathbf{X}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\beta}\right)\right) \mathbb{E}^{1 / 2}\left(\left(v_{\mathbb{M}}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)^{4}\right)<\infty \\
\mathbb{E}\left(\sigma^{2}(\mathbf{X})\left(v_{\mathbb{M}}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)^{2}\right) & \leq \mathbb{E}^{1 / 2}\left(\sigma^{4}(\mathbf{X})\right) \mathbb{E}^{1 / 2}\left(\left(v_{\mathbb{M}}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)^{4}\right)<\infty
\end{aligned}
$$

This completes the proof of the fact that $\operatorname{var}\left(T_{1 n}\right)=O(1 / n)$. Next, wring $\mathbf{Z}_{l, M}=\mathbb{M}^{1 / 2} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{1 / 2} \mathbf{Z}_{l}$, we note that $\left\|\mathbf{X}_{1}^{\top} \mathbb{M} \mathbf{X}_{2}\right\|_{\psi_{1}}^{2} \leq 2\left\|\left\|\mathbf{Z}_{1, \mathbb{M}}+\mathbf{Z}_{2, \mathbb{M}}\right\|_{2}^{2}\right\|_{\psi_{1}}^{2}+2\left\|\left\|\mathbf{Z}_{1, \mathbb{M}}-\mathbf{Z}_{2, \mathbb{M}}\right\|_{2}^{2}\right\|_{\psi_{1}}^{2} \leq 16 \sum_{j=1}^{p}\left\|Z_{1, M}^{2}(j)\right\|_{\psi_{1}}^{2} \leq 16 M^{2} p$ for some $C$ depending on $M$. Therefore for any $k \in \mathbb{N}$ we have $\mathbb{E}\left\{\mathbf{X}_{1}^{\top} \mathbb{M} \mathbf{X}_{2}\right\}^{k} \leq C^{\prime}(M) p^{k / 2}$ for some $C^{\prime}$ depending on $M$. Consequently, we have by Jensen's inequality

$$
\begin{aligned}
\operatorname{var}\left(T_{2 n}\right) & \leq \frac{C}{n^{2}} \mathbb{E}\left(Y_{i}^{2} Y_{j}^{2}\left(\mathbf{X}_{i}^{\top} \mathbb{M} \mathbf{X}_{j}\right)^{2}\right) \\
& =\frac{C}{n^{2}} \mathbb{E}\left[\left\{\sigma^{2}\left(\mathbf{X}_{1}\right) \sigma^{2}\left(\mathbf{X}_{2}\right)+2 \sigma^{2}\left(\mathbf{X}_{1}\right) \phi^{2}\left(\mathbf{X}_{2}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\beta}\right)+\phi^{2}\left(\mathbf{X}_{1}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\beta}\right) \phi^{2}\left(\mathbf{X}_{2}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\beta}\right)\right\}\left\{\mathbf{X}_{1}^{\top} \mathbb{M} \mathbf{X}_{2}\right\}^{2}\right] \\
& \leq \frac{C}{n^{2}} \mathbb{E}^{1 / 2}\left[\left\{\sigma^{2}\left(\mathbf{X}_{1}\right) \sigma^{2}\left(\mathbf{X}_{2}\right)+2 \sigma^{2}\left(\mathbf{X}_{1}\right) \phi^{2}\left(\mathbf{X}_{2}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\beta}\right)+\phi^{2}\left(\mathbf{X}_{1}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\beta}\right) \phi^{2}\left(\mathbf{X}_{2}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\beta}\right)\right\}^{2}\right] \mathbb{E}^{1 / 2}\left[\left(\mathbf{X}_{1}^{\top} \mathbb{M} \mathbf{X}_{2}\right)^{4}\right] \\
& \leq \frac{C^{\prime \prime}(M) p}{n^{2}}
\end{aligned}
$$

for some $C^{\prime \prime}$ depending on $M$. This completes the proof of the lemma.

With Lemma 14, we are ready to prove Lemma 4, and as a direct corollary of Lemma 4, Lemma 2.
Proof of Lemma 4. It is easy to see that to show Lemma 4, it is sufficient to apply Lemma 14 to each individual moment equation in (5) separately. In particular, the proof is complete once one observes that the LHS of each identity in (5) either has the form of $\mathbb{E}\left[\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \mathbf{X} \phi\left(\boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)\right]$ or $\mathbb{E}\left[\phi\left(\boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \mathbf{X}\right)\right]$ with appropriately chosen $\boldsymbol{\alpha}, \boldsymbol{\beta}$, and $\phi$.

# G Unknown Population Covariance Matrix
## G. 1 Linear Models

For notational convenience, we take $\boldsymbol{\mu}=\mathbf{0}$ so the population covariance matrix $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$ is identical to the population Gram matrix $\mathbb{E}\left[\mathbf{X X}^{\top}\right] \equiv \boldsymbol{\Sigma}+\boldsymbol{\mu} \boldsymbol{\mu}^{\top}$. But we consider the situation where the statistician does not know $\boldsymbol{\mu}=\mathbf{0}$. Under the linear model with homoscedastic variance, for estimating the linear and quadratic forms $\lambda_{\beta}=\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\mu}$ and $\gamma_{\beta}^{2}=\boldsymbol{\beta}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma} \boldsymbol{\beta}$, we consider the following estimators without knowing $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$ but under the assumption that the empirical covariance matrix $\widehat{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}}$ is invertible:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \widehat{\lambda}_{\beta}:=\mathbb{U}_{n, 1}[Y] \equiv \frac{1}{n} \mathbf{1}^{\top} \mathbf{Y} \\
& \widehat{\gamma}_{\beta}^{2}:=\frac{1}{n-p}\left\{\mathbf{Y}^{\top}\left(\mathbb{H}-\frac{p}{n} \mathbf{I}\right) \mathbf{Y}\right\}
\end{aligned}
$$

where we denote $\mathbb{X}:=\left(\mathbf{X}_{1}, \cdots, \mathbf{X}_{n}\right)^{\top}$ as the $n \times p$ design matrix, $\mathbb{H}:=\mathbb{X}\left(\mathbb{X}^{\top} \mathbb{X}\right)^{-1} \mathbb{X}$ as the "hat" projection matrix, $\mathbf{Y}:=\left(Y_{1}, \cdots, Y_{n}\right)^{\top} \in \mathbb{R}^{n}$ as the vector collecting the responses over all the subjects, and $\mathbf{1}$ as the $n$-dimensional all-1 vector. The unbiasedness, $\sqrt{n}$-consistency and CAN of $\widehat{\lambda}_{\beta}$ is trivial. The unbiasedness, $\sqrt{n}$-consistency and CAN of $\widehat{\gamma}_{\beta}^{2}$ follow directly from Theorem 1 of Guo and Cheng (2022). $\widehat{\gamma}_{\beta}^{2}$ can also be viewed as approximating a second-order $U$-statistic with the removed diagonal part approximated by $\frac{1}{n} \mathbf{Y}^{\top} \cdot \frac{p}{n-p} \mathbf{I} \cdot \mathbf{Y}$.

For a single coordinate $\beta_{j}$, we consider the following estimator:

$$
\widehat{\beta}_{j}=e_{j}^{\top}\left(\mathbb{X}^{\top} \mathbb{X}\right)^{-1} \mathbb{X}^{\top} \mathbf{Y}
$$

First, $\widehat{\beta}_{j}$ is obviously conditionally, and hence unconditionally, unbiased. We only need to control its variance:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\operatorname{var}\left(\widehat{\beta}_{j}\right) & =\mathbb{E}\left[\operatorname{var}\left(\widehat{\beta}_{j} \mid \mathbb{X}\right)\right]+\operatorname{var}\left(\mathbb{E}\left[\operatorname{var}\left(\widehat{\beta}_{j}\right) \mid \mathbb{X}\right]\right) \\
& =\mathbb{E}\left[\operatorname{var}\left(e_{j}^{\top}\left(\mathbb{X}^{\top} \mathbb{X}\right)^{-1} \mathbb{X}^{\top} \mathbf{Y} \mid \mathbb{X}\right)\right]
\end{aligned}
$$

Then

$$
\operatorname{var}\left(e_{j}^{\top}\left(\mathbb{X}^{\top} \mathbb{X}\right)^{-1} \mathbb{X}^{\top} \mathbf{Y} \mid \mathbb{X}\right)=\sigma^{2} e_{j}^{\top}\left(\mathbb{X}^{\top} \mathbb{X}\right)^{-1} e_{j}
$$

So

$$
\operatorname{var}\left(\widehat{\beta}_{j}\right)=\sigma^{2} e_{j}^{\top} \mathbb{E}\left[\left(\mathbb{X}^{\top} \mathbb{X}\right)^{-1}\right] e_{j}
$$

A common theme of the above estimators is the reliance on the correctness of the homoscedastic linear model. It remains to be seen if a similar strategy can be applied to estimating the moments involved in system of equations such as (5) for GLMs or more general nonlinear models, when $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$ is unknown and $p<n$.

# G. 2 Generalized Linear Models
## G.2.1 The case of $p<n$

In this section, we first prove Proposition 3.
Proof of Proposition 3. In this proof, we take $n / 2$ as $n$ to avoid notation clutter. As a result, the notation in this proof will follow that in Section 3 only. We only need to show that $\tilde{\gamma}_{\beta}^{2}$, as defined in Section 3, is a $\sqrt{n}$-consistent estimator of $\gamma_{\beta}^{2}$. We also let $\boldsymbol{\Omega}:=\boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1}$ and $\tilde{\boldsymbol{\Omega}}:=\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}}^{-1}$ and each element of $\boldsymbol{\Omega}$ and $\tilde{\boldsymbol{\Omega}}$ as, respectively, $\omega_{i, j}$ and $\widetilde{\omega}_{i, j}$ for $i, j \in[p]$.

We first make the following important observation, which is another important implication of the Gaussian design (Couillet and Liao, 2022; Dereziński et al., 2021).
Lemma 15. Under Assumption $\mathbb{G}_{0}$, if $n>p+3$,

$$
\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}} \sim \operatorname{Wishart}_{p}\left(n^{-1} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}, n\right), \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}}^{-1} \equiv \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Omega}} \sim \operatorname{Wishart}_{p}^{-1}\left(n \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \equiv n \boldsymbol{\Omega}, n\right)
$$

where Wishart $_{p}(\mathbf{V}, m)$ and Wishart $_{p}^{-1}(\mathbf{V}, m)$, respectively, denote the $p$-dimensional Wishart and Inverse-Wishart distributions with $m$ degrees-of-freedom and scale matrix $\mathbf{V}$. Thus

$$
\mathbb{E}\left[\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}}^{-1}\right] \equiv \mathbb{E}[\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Omega}}] \equiv \frac{n}{n-p-1} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1}
$$

and for $i, j \in[p]$,

$$
\operatorname{cov}\left(\widetilde{\omega}_{i, j}, \widetilde{\omega}_{k, l}\right)=\frac{2 n^{2} \omega_{i, j} \omega_{k, l}+(n-p-1) n^{2}\left(\omega_{i, k} \omega_{j, l}+\omega_{i, l} \omega_{k, j}\right)}{(n-p)(n-p-1)^{2}(n-p-3)}
$$

It is easy to see that $\widehat{m}_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2}$ is an unbiased estimator of $m_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2}$. We are now left to control its variance. Under Assumption $\mathbb{C}$, the prefactor of (10) has limit $1-\delta$, which can be treated as $O(1)$ without loss of generality. We first note that

$$
\operatorname{var}\left(\widehat{m}_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2}\right)=\operatorname{var}\left(\mathbb{E}\left[\widehat{m}_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2} \mid \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}}\right]\right)+\mathbb{E}\left[\operatorname{var}\left(\widehat{m}_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2} \mid \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}}\right)\right]=: V_{1}+V_{2}
$$

We first control $V_{1}$. Let $\mathbf{v}:=\mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X} Y]$. Following (26), we have

$$
V_{1} \lesssim \operatorname{var}\left(\mathbf{v}^{\top} \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}}^{-1} \mathbf{v}\right)=\sum_{i=1}^{p} \sum_{j=1}^{p} \sum_{k=1}^{p} \sum_{l=1}^{p} v_{i} v_{j} v_{k} v_{l} \operatorname{cov}\left(\widetilde{\omega}_{i, j}, \widetilde{\omega}_{k, l}\right) \lesssim \frac{1}{n}\left(\mathbf{v}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1} \mathbf{v}\right)^{2}
$$

Finally, we control $V_{2}$. Conditioning on $\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}}$, we have, by Hoeffding decomposition and Corollary 1,

$$
\operatorname{var}\left(\widehat{m}_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2} \mid \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}}\right) \lesssim \frac{1}{n}\left(\mathbf{v}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma} \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}}^{-1} \boldsymbol{\Sigma} \mathbf{v}\right)^{2}+\frac{1}{n^{2}} \operatorname{trace}\left(\boldsymbol{\Sigma} \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}}^{-1} \boldsymbol{\Sigma} \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}}^{-1}\right)
$$

Finally, the proof is complete once we marginalize over $\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}}^{-1}$ using (26):

$$
\mathbb{E}\left[\operatorname{var}\left(\widehat{m}_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2} \mid \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}}\right)\right] \lesssim \frac{1}{n}+\frac{p}{n^{2}} \lesssim \frac{1}{n}
$$

# G.2.2 The case of $p \geq n$ 

Proof of Proposition 4.
The constructed estimator as in Section 3.2 crucially relies on the following result on the error of using Chebyshev polynomials to reciprocal $1 / x$.
Lemma 16 (Rephrasing of Lemma 7.8 or Lemma 7.16 of Orecchia et al. (2012)). For any $\epsilon>0$ and $b>a>0$, let $\mathbf{M}$ be a $p \times p$ p.s.d. matrix with eigenvalues bounded between $a$ and $b$. Then, there exists a polynomial $q_{J}(\cdot ; a, b, \epsilon) \equiv q_{J}(\cdot)$ of maximum degree $J$ such that:

$$
\left\|\mathbf{M}^{-1}-q_{J}(\mathbf{M})\right\|_{\mathrm{op}} \lesssim e^{-J}
$$

As a consequence, the following also holds: given any two vectors $\mathbf{v}_{1}, \mathbf{v}_{2} \in \mathbb{R}^{p}$,

$$
\left|\mathbf{v}_{1}^{\top} \mathbf{M}^{-1} \mathbf{v}_{2}-\mathbf{v}_{1}^{\top} q_{J}(\mathbf{M}) \mathbf{v}_{2}\right| \lesssim\left\|\mathbf{v}_{1}\right\|_{2}\left\|\mathbf{v}_{2}\right\|_{2} e^{-J}
$$

In particular, $q_{J}(\cdot)$ can be constructed as follows:

$$
q_{J}(x):=\frac{1}{x}\left(1-\frac{T_{J+1}\left(\frac{b+a-2 x}{b-a}\right)}{T_{J+1}\left(\frac{b+a}{b-a}\right)}\right)
$$

where $T_{J+1}(\cdot)$ is the Chebyshev polynomial of degree $J+1$.
Armed with the above lemma, we can tell that $\widetilde{m}_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2, J(n)}$ with $J(n) \asymp \log \left(\frac{1}{\epsilon}\right)$ and coefficients $\left\{c_{l}, l=0, \cdots, J(n)\right\}$ as specified in $q_{J(n)}$ satisfies:

$$
\left|m_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2}-\widetilde{m}_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2, J(n)}\right| \lesssim \epsilon
$$

Since for each $l=0, \cdots, J(n), \widetilde{m}_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2}^{(l)}$ is an unbiased, $l+2$-th order $U$-statistic estimator of $m_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2}^{(l)}$, we have

$$
\operatorname{var}\left(\widetilde{m}_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2, J(n)}\right) \lesssim \frac{1}{n}\left(\frac{J(n)^{6} \cdot p}{n}\right)^{J(n)+1} \lesssim \frac{1}{n}\left(J(n)^{6} \cdot \delta\right)^{J(n)+1}
$$

following Proposition 7 of Kong and Valiant (2018). One could also obtain a similar variance bound by Lemma 12 of Liu et al. (2017). By choosing, say, $J(n) \asymp(\log n)^{c}$ for some $c$ strictly less than 1 , both the bias and variance still diminish to zero.

## G.2.3 The case of knowing neither $\boldsymbol{\mu}$ nor $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$

Lastly, in this section, we explain how to handle the case where both $\boldsymbol{\mu}$ and $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$ are unknown and need to be estimated from data. Though almost a direct corollary of combining ideas in Sections 2.2 and 3, we decide to spell it out for the sake of completeness. In the accompanying GitHub repository, we have also implemented the method for this general scenario.

We first focus on the case of $p<n / 2$, under Assumption U. We first estimate $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$ by

$$
\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}}:=\frac{1}{\frac{n}{2}-p-1} \sum_{j \in I_{2}}\left(\mathbf{X}_{j}-\overline{\mathbf{X}}_{I_{2}}\right)\left(X_{j}-\overline{\mathbf{X}}_{I_{2}}\right)^{\top}, \text { where } \overline{\mathbf{X}}_{I_{2}}:=\frac{1}{n / 2} \sum_{j \in I_{2}} \mathbf{X}_{j}
$$

Then we construct the same estimator $\widehat{m}_{\mathbf{X} Y, 2}$ as in (10).
For the case of $p \geq n$, we use the approach of approximating reciprocal by Chebyshev polynomials. Since $\gamma_{\beta}^{2(l)}=\mathbb{E}\left[Y \mathbf{X}^{\top}\right] \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{l} \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X} Y]$ involves $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{l}$, we construct the following unbiased higher-order $U$ statistic estimator:

$$
\widehat{\gamma}_{\beta}^{2(l)}=\frac{(n-2 l-2)!}{n!} \sum_{1 \leq i_{1} \neq i_{2} \neq \cdots \neq i_{2 l+1} \neq i_{2 l+2} \leq n} Y_{i_{1}} \mathbf{X}_{i_{1}}^{\top} \prod_{s=1}^{l}\left(\mathbf{X}_{i_{2 s+1}} \mathbf{X}_{i_{2 s+1}}^{\top}-\mathbf{X}_{i_{2 s+1}} \mathbf{X}_{i_{2 s+2}}^{\top}\right) \mathbf{X}_{i_{2}} Y_{i_{2}}
$$

It is worth noting that when $\boldsymbol{\mu}$ is unknown, the involved $U$-statistics have asymmetric kernels, rendering the computation much more complicated as mentioned in Remark 14.

# H. 2 A simulation setting where universality does not hold 

As we mentioned in Remark 10, the delocalization of regression coefficients or conditions alike shall be necessary to establish universality. Therefore, in this section, we conduct numerical experiments where Assumption $\cup(2)$ or Assumption $\cup_{0}(2)$ is violated and demonstrate that the identification strategy based on Gaussian design indeed fails to deliver the correct estimates of the quadratic form or a single coordinate. To this end, we consider the DGP in which $\mathbf{X}_{i, j} \stackrel{\text { i.i.d. }}{\sim} \operatorname{Rad}(1 / 2)$, and $\boldsymbol{\alpha}=(1,0, \cdots, 0)^{\top}$.

The results are summarized in Figures 11 and 12 below. It is clear that our MoM estimators of the quadratic form $\gamma_{\alpha}^{2} \equiv \boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma} \boldsymbol{\alpha}$ and the single coordinate $\alpha_{1}$ are quite different from the true target parameters. For example, speculating Figure 12, the histogram of $\widehat{\alpha}_{1}$ over 500 Monte Carlos does not even cover the true value of $\alpha_{1}$; similarly, the true value of $\gamma_{\alpha}^{2}$ is on the edge of the histogram of $\widehat{\gamma}_{\alpha}^{2}$ over 500 Monte Carlos. Interestingly, when $\lambda$ is relatively large, the debiased estimator of Bellec (2024) has $\sqrt{n} \times$ bias close to 0 , in which case the estimated regression coefficients are mostly very small. It will be interesting to further investigate the effect of $\lambda$ on the bias, variance, and mean squared error of the debiased estimators.

## H. 4 Simulations knowing neither $\boldsymbol{\mu}$ nor $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$

In this section, we further examine the finite sample performance of the proposed moment-based estimators for linear and quadratic forms of GLM parameters under varying knowledge of $\boldsymbol{\mu}$ and $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$, with $p<n / 2$. We focus exclusively on the case of dense regression coefficients and Gaussian designs. We split the sample into two non-overlapping subsamples $I_{1}$ and $I_{2}$ with equal size. We estimate $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$ from $I_{1}$ and then estimate the moments with $U$-statistics from $I_{2}$; afterwards we reverse the roles of $I_{1}$ and $I_{2}$ and implement cross-fitting. Finally we use the cross-fitted moment estimator to estimate the linear form $\boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\mu}$ and the quadratic form $\boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Sigma} \boldsymbol{\alpha}$ of the regression coefficients.

In Figure 17 and Figure 18, we compare four scenarios for estimators of linear form $\boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\mu}$, quadratic form $\|\boldsymbol{\alpha}\|_{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}}^{2}, \alpha_{1}$ and $\alpha_{100}$ : (i) neither $\boldsymbol{\mu}$ nor $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$ is known, (ii) only $\boldsymbol{\mu}$ is known, (iii) only $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$ is known, and (iv) both $\boldsymbol{\mu}$ and $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$ are known.

For the linear form $\boldsymbol{\alpha}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\mu}$ and the quadratic form $\|\boldsymbol{\alpha}\|_{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}}^{2}$ in Figure 17, when $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$ is unknown,

abstract:
In this paper, we consider the estimation of regression coefficients and
signal-to-noise (SNR) ratio in high-dimensional Generalized Linear Models
(GLMs), and explore their implications in inferring popular estimands such as
average treatment effects in high-dimensional observational studies. Under the
``proportional asymptotic'' regime and Gaussian covariates with known
(population) covariance $\Sigma$, we derive Consistent and Asymptotically
Normal (CAN) estimators of our targets of inference through a Method-of-Moments
type of estimators that bypasses estimation of high dimensional nuisance
functions and hyperparameter tuning altogether. Additionally, under
non-Gaussian covariates, we demonstrate universality of our results under
certain additional assumptions on the regression coefficients and $\Sigma$. We
also demonstrate that knowing $\Sigma$ is not essential to our proposed
methodology when the sample covariance matrix estimator is invertible. Finally,
we complement our theoretical results with numerical experiments and
comparisons with existing literature.
